"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693153","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-02","<p>The Treasury welcomes the Competition and Market Authority’s (CMA’s) remedies on Open Banking, which has the potential to bring significant benefits to consumers and SMEs by promoting competition in the retail banking sector.</p><p> </p><p>Responsibility for assessing and monitoring the progress on implementation rests with the independent CMA.</p><p> </p><p>As set out by the CMA, the element of Open Banking dealing with non-personal information must be delivered by 13 March 2017, with the delivery of the full scope by January 2018.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","65017 ; 65018","2017-03-02T11:34:30.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693153/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693153/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693153/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-22","Bank Services: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which regulator will be responsible for monitoring the implementation of the Open Banking Standard.","false","Biography information for Craig Tracey","North Warwickshire","Craig Tracey","65014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693154","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-02","<p>The Treasury is working hard to promote the UK FinTech industry.</p><p> </p><p>At Autumn Statement the government announced specific measures to boost the industry: the Treasury commissioned EY to produce an annual ‘State of UK FinTech’ report on key FinTech metrics to raise the profile of FinTech as an investment opportunity.</p><p> </p><p>The Treasury has also appointed regional FinTech envoys for the Northern Powerhouse and Scotland to build networks and raise awareness of opportunities in these regions - alongside Special Envoy, Eileen Burbidge, whom the Treasury appointed last year to promote the UK FinTech sector at home and abroad.</p><p> </p><p>Together with the Department for International Trade, the Treasury is hosting an International FinTech Conference, on 12 April 2017 in London, to showcase UK FinTech firms to investors from across the globe.</p><p> </p><p>The Treasury is establishing FinTech bridges, which provide opportunities for UK FinTechs that want to scale-up internationally. By establishing links between Government, regulators and private sectors, FinTech Bridges reduce the barriers to entry in new jurisdictions and link UK FinTechs with opportunities for international investment. The UK currently has 3 FinTech Bridges with Singapore, the Republic of Korea and China.</p><p> </p><p>The Treasury is also launching a FinTech Delivery Panel, designed to bring the industry together to develop an overarching FinTech strategy for the UK and to monitor and drive forward FinTech initiatives.</p><p> </p><p>The Government continually engages with the Fintech industry and has not found any significant barriers for innovation arising from bank terms and conditions.</p><p> </p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","65016","2017-03-02T11:32:28.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693154/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693154/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693154/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-22","Financial Services: Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to promote the UK's FinTech industry.","false","Biography information for Craig Tracey","North Warwickshire","Craig Tracey","65015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693156","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-02","<p>This information is not available in the format requested. HM Treasury holds data according to job title, which is not an accurate enough basis to answer the question.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-03-02T11:42:08.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693156/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693156/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693156/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-22","Treasury: Information Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many staff in his Department are employed in media relations and communications roles; and how much was spent on the salaries of such staff members in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","65105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693157","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-02","<p>The latest inheritance tax receipts forecasts for 2016/17 to 2021/22 are published in Table 4.6 of the Office for Budget Responsibility’s <em>Economic and Fiscal Outlook</em> publication at: <a href="http://cdn.budgetresponsibility.org.uk/Nov2016EFO.pdf" target="_blank">http://cdn.budgetresponsibility.org.uk/Nov2016EFO.pdf</a>.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-03-02T15:05:15.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693157/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693157/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693157/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-22","Inheritance Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what forecast his Department has made for the total revenue to the Exchequer raised through inheritance tax in each year to 2020; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","65133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693158","Church Commissioners","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Church Commissioners external contracts are managed either in partnership with the other National Church Institutions through shared office services schemes or by the Corporation of Church House, who manage the building.</p><p>Those that fall specifically within the remit of the Church Commissioners are largely located within the Investments Department, who have five members of staff who oversee external contracts within the property investment team and seven members of staff in the investments team.</p><p> </p>","Meriden","Dame Caroline Spelman",,"2017-03-01T17:55:16.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693158/answer","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693158/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693158/answer",,,,,,,,"9","Church Commissioners","Church Commissioners","2017-02-22","Church Commissioners: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Meriden, representing the Church Commissioners, how many Church Commissioners' staff oversee contracts which have been awarded to external providers.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","64993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693159","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-06","<p>As of 2 March 2017 there are 110 individuals in DCLG with contract management responsibility.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-06T14:35:35.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693159/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693159/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693159/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Department for Communities and Local Government: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many civil servants of his Department oversee contracts which have been awarded to external providers.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","64994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693160","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-02","<p>Rateable values are set independently of Ministers by the Valuation Office Agency.</p><p>Community and amateur sports clubs already receive a mandatory 80 per cent relief on their business rates and local authorities have discretion to top this up. The Government has put in place a £3.6 billion package of transitional relief to support the minority of businesses that do face an increase. We are working closely with the Treasury to determine how best to provide further support to those businesses facing the steepest increases and we expect to be able to make an announcement on this at Budget.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-02T16:52:32.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693160/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693160/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693160/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Non-domestic Rates: Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether transitional funding will be made available to community and amateur sports clubs that will be affected by the increase in business rates.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","65028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693161","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-02","<p>The Government launched an international design competition for a new National Holocaust Memorial and Learning Centre in September 2016 and this is still underway. A jury will select a winning design team in the coming months. The winning design team will work with Government in the months following to further develop their concept design, reflecting comments from technical experts and the general public. The competition brief is clear that the final design should improve the landscape qualities of Victoria Tower Gardens, while respecting and preserving the character and existing use of the Gardens as a public park, including for the use of local residents. The ten submitted designs include an underground learning centre.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-02T16:55:37.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693161/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693161/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693161/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","National Holocaust Memorial Centre and Learning Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of Victoria Tower Gardens will be removed from the use of local residents on a (a) temporary and (b) permanent basis; and what assessment he has made of the extent to which security issues are likely to cause disruption to the subsequent use of Victoria Tower Gardens by local residents.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Leigh","Gainsborough","Sir Edward Leigh","65029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693162","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-02","<p>A £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme will provide support to properties which face an increase in rates. My Department is working closely with the Treasury to determine how best to provide further support to businesses facing the steepest increases. We expect to be in a position to make an announcement on this at the Budget.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-02T17:22:18.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693162/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693162/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693162/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Non-domestic Rates: Coventry South","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to protect small and micro businesses from closure in Coventry South constituency as a result of the planned increase in business rates.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","65032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693163","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-02","<p>The Government believes that widespread free access to cash remains extremely important to the day-to-day lives of many consumers and businesses in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>In 2015 Government set up the Payment Systems Regulator (PSR) with the statutory objective to ensure that the UK’s payment systems, including the LINK ATM scheme, work in the interests of their users. The PSR is monitoring developments within the LINK network and ATM provision in the UK more generally, including assessing the potential effect of any developments on the provision of ATMs in the UK and the possible impact on the scheme’s users.</p><p> </p><p>The PSR has the power to act if LINK or any of its members act in a way that conflicts with any of its objectives.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-03-02T11:38:50.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693163/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693163/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693163/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-22","Cash Dispensing: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to mitigate against the effect of changes to the level of access to free ATMs on high streets and local communities.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","64984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693164","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-01","<p>This information is not held by the department.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-01T17:13:21.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693164/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693164/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693164/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Agency Social Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which regions have used regional memoranda of understanding in order to manage the cost of agency social workers.","false","Biography information for Margaret Beckett","Derby South","Margaret Beckett","65048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693165","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-02","<p>Local authorities receive funds through local taxes, fees and charges, as well as through central government. Local authorities are best placed to take decisions on spend for social care based on local priorities. In response to calls for further funding to tackle the immediate pressures, the Local Government Finance Settlement increased the dedicated funding available for social care through increased flexibility around the social care precept and with a new dedicated £240 million Adult Social Care Support Grant in 2017 to 2018, distributed according to relative need.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-02T16:51:04.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693165/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693165/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693165/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Agency Social Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to tackle the cost to local authorities of agency social workers.","false","Biography information for Margaret Beckett","Derby South","Margaret Beckett","65049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693166","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-02","<p>We do not hold this information, but will consider the data put forward by the Local Government Association as part of our wider Race Equality Audit.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-02T18:11:32.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693166/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693166/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693166/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693166/answer/previousversion/37361","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693166/answer/previousversion/37361",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Councillors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 20 February 2017 to Question 63526, what assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of collecting data on the proportion of local councillors who are (a) women and (b) black, Asian or minority ethnic.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","65008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693167","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-02","<p>The effect of the revaluation of business rates on businesses in Hull and the East Riding of Yorkshire will depend on the specific circumstances and location of the relevant property. A £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme will provide support to properties which face an increase in rates. My Department is working closely with the Treasury to determine how best to provide further support to businesses facing the steepest increases. We expect to be in a position to make an announcement on this at the Budget.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-02T17:17:09.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693167/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693167/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693167/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Non-domestic Rates: East Riding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of businesses in (a) Hull and (b) the East Riding of Yorkshire that will see their business rates (i) increase and (ii) decrease relative to previous years as a result of business rates revaluation.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","65057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693168","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-16","<p>The effect of the revaluation of business rates on businesses in Hackney will depend on the specific circumstances and location of the relevant property.</p><p>We announced further measures to support businesses in last week's Budget.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-16T13:46:06.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693168/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693168/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693168/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693168/answer/previousversion/37364","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693168/answer/previousversion/37364",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Non-domestic Rates: Hackney","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of the effect of the revaluation of business rates on businesses in Hackney.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","65083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693169","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-27","<p>Following a meeting about possible unitary reorganisation which the Dorset leaders had in late 2015 with my Rt Hon Friend Greg Clark, the then Secretary of State, officials have provided information, largely orally, to the 9 Dorset councils as those councils together developed and took forward options for reorganisation. This information focussed on such matters as the process for unitarisation, the issues councils considering making a proposal for reorganisation might need to address, and the type of evidence and information which might need to be included in any such proposal.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-27T17:25:12.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693169/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693169/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693169/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Local Government: Dorset","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether Officials of his Department will provide advice and guidance to the Leaders of Christchurch Borough Council, East Dorset District Council and Purbeck District Council in relation to their preparation of an alternative submission for local government reorganisation in Dorset.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","65073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693170","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-27","<p>I refer the Hon Member to my answer today to Question UIN 65073.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-27T17:31:24.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693170/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693170/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693170/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Local Government: Dorset","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the letter of 9 February 2017 from the six leaders to the Secretary of State, titled Future Dorset: Proposals for the Reorganisation of Local Government, published on his Department's website, what advice and guidance was provided by Paul Rowsell, Ian Barber and Victoria Jones to the Leaders of Bournemouth Borough Council, Dorset County Council, North Dorset District Council, Borough of Poole, West Dorset District Council and Weymouth & Portland District Council on proposals for local government reorganisation in Dorset.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","65074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693171","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-01","<p>I met the senior representatives of the 9 Dorset councils, including the then deputy leader of Christchurch Borough Council, on 30 November 2016, when the 9 councils discussed with me the proposal which they were intending to submit and which in the event, 6 of the councils have now submitted. I intend now to consider carefully that proposal before announcing how I am minded to proceed, after which there will be an opportunity for the councils and others interested to make representations.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-01T14:28:07.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693171/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693171/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693171/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693171/answer/previousversion/37362","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693171/answer/previousversion/37362",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Local Government: Dorset","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will meet the Leader of Christchurch Borough Council to discuss that Council's proposals for local government reorganisation in Dorset.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","65075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693172","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-16","<p>My Department's central communications function is responsible for media relations and external communications. At 28 February 2017, 26.9 full time equivalent staff were employed in this team. In relation to salaries, the information is not held centrally for the time period requested and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-16T14:22:46.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693172/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693172/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693172/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Department for Communities and Local Government: Information Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many staff in his Department are employed in media relations and communications roles; and how much was spent on the salaries of such staff members in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","65101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693173","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-02","<p>A £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme will provide support to businesses, including those in rural areas, which face an increase in rates. My Department is working closely with the Treasury to determine how best to provide further support to businesses facing the steepest increases. We expect to be in a position to make an announcement on this at the Budget.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-02T17:48:46.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693173/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693173/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693173/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Non-domestic Rates: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans he has to provide support to businesses in rural areas affected by increases in business rates.","false","Biography information for Kevin Hollinrake","Thirsk and Malton","Kevin Hollinrake","65225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693174","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-02","<p>A £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme will provide support to properties which face an increase in rates. My Department is working closely with the Treasury to determine how best to provide further support to businesses facing the steepest increases. We expect to be in a position to make an announcement on this at the Budget.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-02T16:53:07.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693174/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693174/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693174/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Small Businesses: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Prime Minister of 22 February 2017, how the hardest cases of small businesses that are particularly affected by the business rates revaluation will be defined and identified; how appropriate relief will be calculated; for how long such relief will apply; how much new funding will be made available for transitional relief; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","65228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693175","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-02","<p>The information the Hon Member has requested is included in the Government’s response to the consultation on the transitional relief scheme, published online at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/business-rates-revaluation-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/business-rates-revaluation-2017</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-02T17:14:44.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693175/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693175/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693175/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how the transitional relief scheme for business rate revaluation will be funded; and what assessment he has made of how that relief scheme will affect businesses in northern England.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","65203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693176","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-02","<p>The effect of the revaluation of business rates on businesses in areas where there is population of 10,000 or less and 3,000 or less will depend on the specific circumstances and location of the relevant property. A £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme will provide support to properties which face an increase in rates. My Department is working closely with the Treasury to determine how best to provide further support to businesses facing the steepest increases. We expect to be in a position to make an announcement on this at the Budget.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-02T16:48:58.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693176/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693176/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693176/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect of the changes in business rates on businesses located in areas where there is population of (a) 10,000 or less and (b) 3,000 or less.","false","Biography information for Kevin Hollinrake","Thirsk and Malton","Kevin Hollinrake","65204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693177","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-07","<p>The data held by the Valuation Office Agency is not broken down by population size, so it is not possible to produce the statistics requested on rateable values in areas where the population is (a) 10,000 or less and (b) 3,000 or less.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-07T17:26:15.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693177/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693177/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693177/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-22","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will publish the data included in the table produced for non-domestic rating: 2010 and 2017 revaluation rateable values by country, region and SCat code for business located in areas where the population is (a) 10,000 or less and (b) 3,000 or less.","false","Biography information for Kevin Hollinrake","Thirsk and Malton","Kevin Hollinrake","65205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693179","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-02","<p>Government is committed to ensuring that all children and young people, particularly those who are currently least active or from under-represented groups, have the best opportunities to engage in sport and physical activity.</p><p><br> The Secretary of State regularly meets the Secretary of State for Education. Our Departments work closely together on school sport, including through the Ministerial School Sport Board which I attend along with the Minister for Vulnerable Children and Families and the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Public Health and Innovation.</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-03-02T14:43:08.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693179/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693179/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693179/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-22","Schools: Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Education on increasing the number of children participating in sport in schools.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","65121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693180","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-28","<p>The Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) set out in Sporting Future are measures that will track progress and trends over time, against the key outputs defined in the strategy. The KPIs are not set targets with a defined end date.</p><p> </p><p>The timeline for reporting on those KPIs in Sporting Future where data is not already available, is provided in the Sporting Future First Annual Report.</p><p> </p><p>There are a number of sources of data for the KPIs, and some of those sources, such as Active Lives Children, are still in development. Figures against these KPIs will be published in future annual reports.</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-02-28T16:59:46.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693180/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693180/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693180/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-22","Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what her Department's timescale is for meeting each of the key performance indicators in her Department's report, Sporting Future: First Annual Report, published on 9 February 2017.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","65209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693181","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-02","<p>We announced on 27 February that we would lead a cross-Government initiative on internet safety. We will be convening a series of round-table discussions with social media companies, technology firms, young people, charities and mental health experts to examine online risks and how to tackle them. The round tables are also expected to examine concerns around issues like trolling and other aggressive behaviour which impact on politicians and citizens more generally.</p><p>The Department for Education (DfE) launched the new computing curriculum, includes digital literacy, in September 2014. DfE has provided additional funding for digital skills through The Good Things Foundation, funding 680,000 people since 2014.</p><p>Government is also introducing a digital entitlement to ensure that publicly funded digital training to people who are over the age of 19 and do not have such skills.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-02T16:36:52.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693181/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693181/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693181/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-22","Speaker's Commission On Digital Democracy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the recommendations of the WebRoots Democracy report, Democracy 2.0: Hitting refresh on the Digital Democracy Commission, published on 26 January 2017, whether the Government plans to commission a review on the widespread internet abuse of politicians and citizens online; and what steps her Department is taking to ensure that (a) young people leave school digitally literate and (b) adults of all ages are educated in digital literacy.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","65031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693182","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-27","<p>We are looking at options for increasing public access to the Government Art Collection (GAC). Around two-thirds of the collection's holdings of over 14,000 works of art are already on display in more than 370 buildings at home and abroad promoting the UK and its art. For example, an exhibition from the Collection will be held in Hull during its tenure as the UK City of Culture.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-27T16:24:30.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693182/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693182/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693182/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-22","Government Art Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to ensure that items from the Government Art Collection are displayed where they can be readily viewed by communities around the country.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","65036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693183","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","true","2017-02-27","<p>A list of the locations in which items from the Government Art Collection have been shown in the last 12 months is attached.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-27T17:42:07.94Z","2017-03-01T11:19:15.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693183/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693183/answer","GAC PQ 65037 amended.docx","List of Locations - Amended - Additions in Red ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693183/answer","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693183/answer/previousversion/37353","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693183/answer/previousversion/37353","GAC PQ 65037 list.pdf","List of locations the GAC has been shown ","10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-22","Government Art Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, in which locations items from the Government Art Collection have been shown in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","65037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693184","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-27","<p>The UK City of Culture and European Capital of Culture programmes are designed to use culture as a catalyst for economic and social regeneration and to raise the profile of arts and creativity locally, nationally and internationally. Success in these competitions also helps areas to develop a broader high quality arts and culture sector, as well as attract increased business investment and boost tourism. DCMS is using the competitions now running to identify the UK City of Culture 2021 and European Capital of Culture 2023 to highlight these benefits to local areas, including through briefing events that bring together areas that have bid in previous competitions.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-27T16:20:08.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693184/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693184/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693184/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-22","European City of Culture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to promote cooperation between cities that have won UK or European City of Culture competitions to raise cultural awareness across the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","65079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693186","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-17","<p><br>We are committed to delivering superfast broadband and better mobile connectivity to the United Kingdom. In the constituency of Chipping Barnet over 97% of the constituency can currently get superfast broadband from a diverse range of suppliers. More than 4.3 million homes and businesses have now been reached by the Government’s nationwide rollout of superfast broadband. Through the Government’s Better Broadband Scheme <a href="https://basicbroadbandchecker.culture.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://basicbroadbandchecker.culture.gov.uk/</a> all homes and businesses can now access better broadband (speeds of 2 Megabits per second). To ensure that no one is left behind, the Government is also introducing a new broadband Universal Service Obligation (USO) within this Parliament. The USO will give households and businesses the legal right to request a broadband connection with speeds of at least 10 Megabits, no matter where they live or work.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-17T14:47:19.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693186/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693186/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693186/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-22","Broadband: Chipping Barnet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to improve access to high-speed broadband in suburban areas such as Chipping Barnet.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","64982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693187","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-02","<p>It is the responsibility of individual teams across the Department to manage contracts and maintain the appropriate level of oversight consistent with the value, strategic importance and levels of risk associated with individual contracts.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-02T16:38:12.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693187/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693187/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693187/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-22","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many civil servants of her Department oversee contracts which have been awarded to external providers.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","64995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693188","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-27","<p>As announced in the July 2015 Budget, the Government is committed to spending 2% of GDP on Defence for the rest of this decade. The Defence Budget will rise by 0.5% above inflation each year to 2020-21 and we also have access to up to £1.5 billion per year from the Joint Security Fund. In line with NATO guidelines, we will continue to ensure we capture all spending that supports the defence of the United Kingdom.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2017-02-27T16:30:09.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693188/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693188/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693188/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-22","Defence: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how he plans to ensure that the Government spends the equivalent of at least two per cent of GDP per year for the rest of this Parliament on defence.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","65132"
