"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693218","Department for Education","false","2017-02-27","<p>We have no concerns regarding financial management at Sandymoor Free School and the Trust does not have a financial deficit.</p><p> </p><p>On educational attainment, whilst the school received a good judgement from Ofsted in January 2014 it remains an academy of concern. The Progress 8 score in summer 2016 was -1.1 which is significantly below the LA average of 0.19 and the national average of 0. Only 33% of pupils achieved Grade C or above in English &amp; maths (LA: 60.2%, National: 59.3%).</p><p> </p><p>The pension deficit of the Trust for 2015/16 is £295,000.</p><p> </p><p>The latest published financial statements for Sandymoor Free School 2015/16 show a cumulative carry forward surplus of £197,632.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","65077 ; 65091","2017-02-27T16:51:12.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693218/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693218/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693218/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Sandymoor School","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the level of financial deficit of Sandymoor Free School in Runcorn was for the last year for which financial accounts were submitted.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","65092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693219","Department for Education","false","2017-02-27","<p>School-level figures for spending per pupil are published annually. The most recent figures are available at: <a href="https://www.compare-school-performance.service.gov.uk/download-data" target="_blank">https://www.compare-school-performance.service.gov.uk/download-data</a> (for maintained schools in financial year 2015-16, select: a) the academic year 2015 to 2016; b) data for All of England; and c) Spend per pupil (full dataset)), and at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/income-and-expenditure-in-academies-in-england-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/income-and-expenditure-in-academies-in-england-2014-to-2015</a> (for academy schools in academic year 2014/15).</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-27T14:19:45.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693219/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693219/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693219/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Pupils: Halton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the average funding per pupil has been in each secondary school in Halton in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","65090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693220","Home Office","false","2017-02-28","<p>The number of educational institutions which have had their Tier 4 sponsor licence revoked between 1 May 2010 and up to 7 October 2014 is available and can be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/tier-4-sponsors-whose-status-appeared-as-revoked-from-2010-to-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/tier-4-sponsors-whose-status-appeared-as-revoked-from-2010-to-2014</a></p><p> </p><p>This means that these institutions cannot bring in non-EEA students to study in the UK under the Tier 4 route. The Home Office is planning to publish up to date data shortly.</p><p> </p><p>Revoking an institution’s Tier 4 sponsor licence does not prevent them from operating.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-28T09:51:30.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693220/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693220/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693220/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-22","Further Education: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer given by the Prime Minister to Question 58 at the Liaison Committee meeting on 20 December 2016, how many colleges have ceased to operate since 2010 because they have been found to be not offering an education; and if she will place a list of those colleges in the Library.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","65087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693221","Department for Education","false","2017-02-27","<p>In the 2016 secondary school application round non-faith school first preferences to offers ratio was 0.98. For faith schools the ratio was 1.08.</p><p>The data, which the Department collects on admissions and school choice, does not enable an assessment to be made as to the specific reason why parents are more likely to make faith schools their first preference.</p><p>There are often a range of factors that affect how parents choose a particular school, such as location, type of school, whether a sibling already attends, feeder arrangements, reputation and Ofsted rating. It is therefore not possible to make a precise assessment as to what is the main reason why parents are more likely to make a faith school their first preference.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-27T17:30:01.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693221/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693221/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693221/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Faith Schools: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the article in The Times of 14 February 2017 in the name of the Minister of State for School Standards, what the evidential basis is for her statement that there is significant parental demand for good faith schools; and whether she has made an assessment of such demand being for faith schools rather than for good schools.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","65088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693222","Department for Education","false","2017-02-27","<p>Resources for maintained nursery schools are not fixed but are drawn from across the directorate and the wider department and are allocated to reflect demand.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-27T17:36:02.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693222/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693222/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693222/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Pre-school Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many full-time equivalent officials of her Department are working on maintained nursery policies.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","65100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693223","Department for Education","false","2017-04-27","<p>The decision to start the sale process for part of the student loan book (set out in Written Statement HCWS458) is based on a robust and comprehensive assessment of the market which showed that it has a good prospect of achieving value for money.</p><p>As part of assessing value for money, the Government compares the value of keeping the student loan book and receiving uncertain and fluctuating repayments over time, and selling the rights to the remaining future repayments made on the student loan book and receiving a fixed sum of money for them now.</p><p>The sale process itself is also designed to achieve the best possible price for the taxpayer.</p><p>A further assessment will be made before the sale is completed (and before any further sales).</p><p>As required by the Sale of Student Loans Act 2008, the Government will provide a report to Parliament on the sale arrangements within three months of sale completion. As required by the Act, this report will make reference to value for money.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-04-27T07:59:03.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693223/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693223/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693223/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Written Statement of 6 February 2017, HCWS458, what assessment she has made of whether the sale of part of the English student loan book will deliver value for money; and if she will publish the framework used to make that assessment.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","65153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693224","Department for Education","false","2017-04-27","<p>Pursuant to Written Statement HCWS458, the proposed sale will comprise the future repayments on the outstanding balances on a selection of English student loans which became eligible for repayment between 2002 and 2006. A loan enters repayment the April after the student has left their course.</p><p>A securitisation structure will be used for the sale to enable the Government to maximise value for money for the taxpayer. Under this structure, the loans will be sold to a new independent English-domiciled company - the Issuer - whose sole purpose is to own the loans on behalf of investors. Investors will purchase notes issued by the Issuer and the Issuer will make payments on the notes using the repayments made on the underlying loans.</p><p>The sale is a competitive process open to all eligible investors. The different tranches of notes are expected to be attractive to a range of potential investors, thereby promoting an efficient market and efficient pricing. We anticipate insurers, pension funds and alternative asset managers, among others, will be interested.</p><p>Investors would have no right to change any of the current loan arrangements or to contact people with student loans.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-04-27T08:00:31.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693224/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693224/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693224/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Written Statement of 6 February 2017, HCWS458, what criteria will be used to assess the suitability of the buyer of the part of the English student loan book that the Government plans to sell.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","65154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693226","Department for Education","false","2017-02-28","<p>The National Curriculum was comprehensively reviewed and then published in 2013. We currently have no plans to review it. Schools started teaching the majority of the new National Curriculum in September 2014, with some subjects taught from September 2015 and the final subject, science at Key Stage 4, taught from September 2016. Schools are therefore currently embedding the new National Curriculum into their teaching. The National Curriculum outlines the body of essential knowledge that must be taught in maintained schools. This essential knowledge should not change significantly over time.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-28T16:32:35.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693226/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693226/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693226/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Curriculum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she plans for changes to the national curriculum; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","64946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693227","Department for Education","false","2017-04-25","<p>The new National Curriculum, introduced from September 2014, sets out the essential knowledge in the key subjects that must be taught to children of compulsory school age in maintained schools in England. Academies and free schools are required to teach a balanced and broadly based curriculum and can use the National Curriculum as a benchmark, as it sets out a knowledge based, ambitious, academically rigorous curriculum.</p><p>The National Curriculum explicitly sets out this essential knowledge by subject rather than grouping it by broader cross-curricula topics. Securing a sound foundation of subject knowledge is essential to enabling pupils from all backgrounds to succeed in their education. Schools and teachers use their professional judgement about how this knowledge should be taught and what should be included in the wider curriculum to meet the needs of their pupils.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-25T15:49:02.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693227/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693227/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693227/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Curriculum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on promoting a cross-curriculum approach to teaching; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","64947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693228","Department for Education","false","2017-02-28","<p>All schools, including academies and free schools, must provide a broad and balanced curriculum that promotes the spiritual, moral, cultural, mental and physical development of pupils at the school and of society.</p><p>The new National Curriculum, introduced in 2014, sets out the essential knowledge in the key subjects that schools should teach. In Key Stages 1 to 3, music and art and design are statutory subjects for maintained schools. At Key Stage 4, all pupils in maintained schools must be offered the opportunity to study at least one subject in the arts ‘entitlement’ area, which includes art and design, music, dance, drama, and media arts.</p><p>Beyond the curriculum, we are investing £300 million of ring-fenced funding in music hubs in 2016-20. This is intended to ensure all children, whatever their background, have access to a high quality music education, including learning to play musical instruments and having the opportunity to play and sing in ensembles.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-28T16:27:31.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693228/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693228/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693228/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Arts: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to ensure the integration of creative arts into mainstream education.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","64944"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693229","Department for Education","false","2017-03-08","<p>The data required is published in the 16-18 School Performance Tables[1].</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] Derived from School Performance Tables available at</p><p><a href="https://www.compare-school-performance.service.gov.uk/download-data?currentstep=datatypes&amp;regiontype=all&amp;la=0&amp;downloadYear=2015-2016&amp;datatypes=ks5underlying" target="_blank">https://www.compare-school-performance.service.gov.uk/download-data?currentstep=datatypes&amp;regiontype=all&amp;la=0&amp;downloadYear=2015-2016&amp;datatypes=ks5underlying</a></p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-08T15:17:57.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693229/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693229/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693229/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Politics: GCE A-level","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which post-16 education institutions by school type entered pupils for an A-level in government and politics in 2016.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","64952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693230","Department for Education","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Department for Education will be publishing an early years workforce strategy in due course, which will seek to remove the barriers to attracting, retaining and developing staff. The strategy will include a focus on what government can do to help grow the graduate workforce.</p><p>We make early years initial teacher training places available to meet the demand from the market. Funding is available for training course fees, with additional funding for nursery employers to help them support graduates in their setting to become early years teachers. To encourage the best graduates into the early years workforce we provide bursaries to eligible trainees.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-03-01T17:10:36.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693230/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693230/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693230/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Pre-school Education: Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make an assessment of the potential implications for her policies of the results of polling commissioned by Save the Children, published in February 2017, on the majority of parents wanting the Government to ensure that every nursery in England has a qualified early years teacher.","false","Biography information for Mr Graham Allen","Nottingham North","Mr Graham Allen","64949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693231","Department for Education","false","2017-03-01","<p>Reaching a high level of fluency in reading and writing by the end of primary school is fundamental to achievement in education and critical for everyday life. We want all children, regardless of their background, to leave primary school able to read and write to a high standard.</p><p>The Early Years Foundation Stage (EYFS) sets the standards for the provision of development and care from birth to age five. This includes a focus on literacy, communication and language. The EYFS Profile results have shown an increase in the percentage of children achieving a good level of development – from 51.7% in 2013 to 69% in 2016.</p><p>The results from the 2016 EYFS Profile show that 72.1% of children achieved at least the expected level in all early learning goals in literacy in 2016 compared with 60.7% in 2013. For communication and language 81.6% of children achieved at least the expected level in all learning goals in communication and language compared to 72.2% in 2013.</p><p>The English curriculum introduced in 2014 places a renewed focus on phonics, as evidence shows that systematic synthetic phonics is the most effective approach to teaching young children to read.</p><p> </p><p>To boost the quality of phonics teaching, we provided £23.7 million in match funding to over 14,000 primary schools, enabling them to buy systematic synthetic phonics products and training. The results from this year’s phonics screening check show that, since the introduction of the phonics check in 2012, over 147,000 more six year olds are now on track to become excellent readers. Almost 9 in 10 pupils (89%) who met the expected standard of phonic decoding in year 1 went on to reach the expected standard in reading at the end of Key Stage 1.</p><p> </p><p>The Year 7 Catch-up Premium provides additional funding for secondary schools to support pupils who did not reach the expected level in reading and/or mathematics by the end of primary school.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-01T15:46:11.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693231/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693231/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693231/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Basic Skills: Primary Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make an assessment of the potential implications for her policies of data published by Save the Children in February 2017 on the number of children at risk of finishing primary school without important skills in English by 2020.","false","Biography information for Mr Graham Allen","Nottingham North","Mr Graham Allen","64950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693232","Department for Education","false","2017-03-02","<p>This information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-03-02T11:55:58.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693232/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693232/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693232/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Department for Education: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many civil servants of her Department oversee contracts which have been awarded to external providers.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","64996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693233","Department for Education","false","2017-02-27","<p>The decision to start the sale process for the student loan book (set out in Written Statement HCWS458) was based on a robust and comprehensive assessment of the market which showed that it has a good prospect of achieving value for money.</p><p>An in-depth market testing exercise suggested there was strong interest in this type of long-term, inflation-linked asset. Conditions in the equity and debt markets remain strong.</p><p>The Government will continue to monitor market conditions carefully to ensure we get a fair price and secure value for money for taxpayers.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-02-27T17:54:40.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693233/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693233/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693233/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate her Department has made of the effect of the vote to leave the EU on the value of the student loan book; and whether that estimate affected her decision to sell it.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","65006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693234","Department for Education","false","2017-02-27","<p>The proposed sale of the student loan book, set out in Written Statement HCWS458, gives the Government the capacity to invest in other policies with greater economic or social returns and reduces fiscal pressures.</p><p>The position of students and graduates, including those with loans in scope of the sale, will not be affected by the sale.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-02-27T17:53:58.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693234/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693234/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693234/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the potential (a) short-term and (b) long-term benefits are of selling the student loan book for (i) the taxpayer, (ii) students with outstanding loans and (iii) current and future students.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","65007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693235","Department for Education","false","2017-02-28","<p>The criteria used to determine eligibility for multi-year allocations are set out in the 2017-18 allocations methodology published in September 2016. For postgraduate providers, these include Ofsted grade (based on published initial teacher education inspection data) but do not refer to provider size or location.</p><p> </p><p>We will publish a detailed technical methodology on how three-year allocations were determined, alongside a full list of allocations for 2017-18, in due course.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-28T14:41:23.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693235/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693235/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693235/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what account her Department took of the (a) location, (b) size and (c) date of the latest Ofsted inspection of university providers when awarding universities either a multi-year or single-year allocation of initial teacher training places.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","65052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693236","Department for Education","false","2017-02-28","<p>To teach in a state maintained secondary, primary, or state or non-state maintained special school you must have qualified teacher status (QTS). Routes that lead to the award of QTS, including those which assess previous teaching experience, are outlined on the Get Into Teaching website:</p><p><a href="https://getintoteaching.education.gov.uk/explore-my-options/teacher-training-routes" target="_blank">https://getintoteaching.education.gov.uk/explore-my-options/teacher-training-routes</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Teachers who trained outside England may be able to have their teaching qualification recognised as equivalent to QTS. To do so, such teachers must apply to the National College for Teaching and Leadership (NCTL) to be awarded QTS before they can take up a teaching post in a maintained school or non-maintained special school in England. Individuals who hold qualified teacher learning and skills (QTLS) status are also eligible to work as a qualified teacher in schools in England.</p><p>Further information on eligibility and equivalencies is available on GOV.UK: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/qualified-teacher-status-qts" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/qualified-teacher-status-qts</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-28T16:38:24.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693236/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693236/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693236/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what routes her Department recognises as providing appropriate entry into the teaching profession.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","65053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693237","Department for Education","false","2017-02-27","<p>Our proposals for funding reform will mean that schools and local authority areas will, for the first time, receive a consistent and fair share of the schools budget, so that they can give every child the opportunity to reach their full potential.</p><p> </p><p>For Sheffield local authority, the proposals would mean an increase in schools funding of 4.6%. On funding for pupils with high needs, Sheffield local authority would see an increase of 13.0%.</p><p> </p><p>The current consultation is open until 22 March, and we are keen to hear views from as many schools, governors, local authorities and parents as possible. We will publish our response to the consultation, including details of representations received, in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-27T14:21:22.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693237/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693237/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693237/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Schools: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment her Department has made of the effect of changes to school funding on schools in Sheffield.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","65012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693238","Department for Education","false","2017-03-01","<p>This information is not available in the format requested.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-03-01T16:12:15.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693238/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693238/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/693238/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-22","Children in Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and which (a) primary and (b) secondary schools in England had (i) between 10 and 20 and (ii) more than 20 looked-after children attending such schools in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","64985"
