ionals Abroad: Voting Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to A democracy that works for everyone: British citizens overseas, a policy statement, published on 7 October 2016, whether increased staff time and resources were a criterion in determining the amount of additional funding to be provided to electoral registration officers in relation to the removal of the 15-year time limit on British citizens living abroad being able to vote in elections.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","64729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692437","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-02-28","<p><strong>I refer the honourable member to the letter sent to her office on 27 February by the Leader of the House of Commons, and reiterate the apologies in that letter for the delay related to the changes in Ministry of Government. </strong></p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-02-28T13:36:42.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692437/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692437/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692437/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-02-21","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, when he plans to respond to the letter of 1 June 2016 relating to a mock vote in the House originally addressed to the then Prime Minister, which was transferred to his Department and then to the Department for Exiting the European Union, which has declined to reply to the correspondence as it pre-dates that Department's existence.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","64790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692438","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-02","<p>The Financial Reporting Council assessed asset owners based on the quality of their written statement of compliance with the Stewardship Code.</p><p> </p><p>The Stewardship Code is available at <a href="http://www.frc.org.uk/Our-Work/Publications/Corporate-Governance/UK-Stewardship-Code-September-2012.pdf" target="_blank">www.frc.org.uk/Our-Work/Publications/Corporate-Governance/UK-Stewardship-Code-September-2012.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The Trustees’ Secretariat are revising their statement of compliance to more accurately reflect the stewardship work that is currently being undertaken by the PCPF. The Fund aims to achieve tier 1 status once this work is complete.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-03-02T13:26:13.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692438/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692438/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692438/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-21","Parliamentary Contributory Pension Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, for what reasons the Financial Reporting Council placed the Parliamentary Contributory Pension Fund in the secondary tier for compliance with the Financial Stewardship code; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","64885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692439","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>The professional investment advisors appointed by the Parliamentary Contributory Pension Fund Trustees are Hymans Robertson.</p><p>They have been employed by the PCPF Trustees as their professional investment advisors since 2008. The Trustees follow standard public procurement guidelines to appoint all professional advisors to the Fund.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-03-01T10:12:30.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692439/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692439/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692439/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-21","Parliamentary Contributory Pension Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 14 February 2017 to Question 63244, from which organisations or individuals the Trustees of the Parliamentary Contributory Pension Fund (PCPF) sought professional advice regarding the long-term risks to the financial performance of the PCPF of that fund's investments in the fossil fuel extractive industry.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","64917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692440","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-01","<p>Ministers hold regular meetings with a wide range of stakeholders, including from the alcohol industry, with a number of these meetings having taken place in recent weeks.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-03-01T16:01:06.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692440/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692440/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692440/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-21","Alcoholic Drinks: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, for what reason Treasury Ministers will not hold pre-Budget meetings with representatives of the alcohol industry in 2017.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","64828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692441","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-24","<p>After making payments of over £1.1billion to more than 900,000 policyholders, the Payment Scheme has now closed. There are no plans to reopen the Payment Scheme.</p><p> </p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-02-24T12:09:02.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692441/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692441/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692441/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-21","Equitable Life Assurance Society: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make further payments to people affected by regulatory failings at Equitable Life.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","64869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692443","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-24","<p>While significant numbers of customers are not affected, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) had identified some issues with the self-assessment tax calculation. These related to Class 2 National Insurance contributions and the Marriage Allowance.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC has either fixed these issues directly or has adopted processes to deal with them effectively.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-24T12:56:54.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692443/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692443/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692443/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-21","Taxation: Rebates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, for what reason HM Revenue and Customs experienced difficulties with the 2015-16 tax calculation producing correct repayments due for that year; and when those difficulties are likely to be resolved.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","64856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692445","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-01","<p>It is not possible to separately identify the figure for late submission of tax returns, but in 2015-16 the total accrued revenue for all fines and penalties was £1.0 billion. This is reported on page 160 of HM Revenue and Customs’ Annual Report and Accounts, which are available to view at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hmrc-annual-report-and-accounts-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hmrc-annual-report-and-accounts-2015-to-2016</a>.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-03-01T15:51:09.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692445/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692445/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692445/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-21","Taxation: Self-assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much has been accrued to the public purse from fines levied by HM Revenue and Customs for late submission of tax returns in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692446","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-24","<p>Automatic enrolment was designed to help more people save for their retirement, including groups who historically have been less likely to save, such as women and lower earners. The policy is working, with over 7.3 million people enrolled by the end of January 2017. Around two thirds of women are in the eligible target population for automatic enrolment and 10 million workers are estimated to be newly saving or saving more as a result of Automatic Enrolment by 2018, of which 3.6 million are women.</p><p> </p><p>Since the introduction of automatic enrolment, the private sector has seen the largest increases in participation in workplace pensions and by 2014 there was no gender gap in participation. As of 2015 female participation in the private sector had actually risen to a slightly higher level of 70 per cent compared to 69 per cent for male eligible employees. This represents a 30 percentage point increase for women from 2012 (whilst participation for men has increased by 26 percentage points) continuing the upward trend since the introduction of automatic enrolment.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Government’s decision to freeze the value of the automatic enrolment earnings trigger at £10,000 in 2017/18 is estimated to result in around 70,000 extra people being brought into automatic enrolment of whom around 50,000 (75 per cent) are women.</p><p> </p><p>As part of my Department’s review of automatic enrolment, which we have embarked on this year, we will look at how we can build on its success so that it continues to meet the needs of individual savers, including women. In addition to considering those not currently benefitting from the policy, this review will look at strengthening the evidence base concerning future contributions, and how we can maximise engagement with work place pension saving.</p><p>The government believes that employee share ownership in its various forms can help drive productivity and increase employee engagement. To support employee share ownership the government provides four tax-advantaged employee share schemes, which provide certain tax benefits for individuals acquiring shares in the company they work for.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-02-24T13:22:29.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692446/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692446/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692446/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-21","Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps are being taken to ensure that more women participate in pension schemes and company share ownerships.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","64798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692447","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-24","<p>Automatic enrolment works by requiring employers to enrol all eligible jobholders in to a workplace pension and make a contribution into it. Eligible jobholders do not need to apply to be automatically enrolled. However, those who are not eligible can ask to join their employer’s pension, known as ‘opting-in’, if they choose. Eligible employees are those who are aged 22 to State Pension age; earn £10,000 per year or more; are not already in a qualifying pension scheme and; who ordinarily work in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>Automatic enrolment has been a great success with 7.3 million people enrolled at the end of January 2017. Automatic enrolment is being rolled-out gradually from October 2012 – February 2018 starting with the largest employers down to the smallest. We do not have the data that would show the ratio of men to women within the cohort of people who have already been automatically enrolled. However, there is data available that shows the increases in participation since automatic enrolment began in 2012.</p><p> </p><p>In 2012, overall participation of female eligible employees was 58 per cent, compared to male participation at 52 per cent. In 2015, the participation of female eligible employees was 78 per cent with overall male participation at 73 per cent.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-02-24T13:12:19.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692447/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692447/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692447/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-21","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information his Department holds on the ratio of men to women who have applied for auto-enrolment pensions.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","64799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692448","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-01","<p>GOV.UK Verify will be the single identification service for individuals. The authentication service that HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is developing to replace the Government Gateway will complement the existing GOV.UK Verify service for business representatives.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC agreed with the Cabinet Office and Department for Work and Pensions to take on responsibility for decommissioning the existing Government Gateway, in line with current contractual arrangements, by March 2018. HMRC and the Government Digital Service are working with government departments to help them find suitable solutions beyond that point.</p><p>The cost of building a replacement Gateway service is commercially sensitive information, and so cannot be provided.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","64721 ; 64722","2017-03-01T15:53:59.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692448/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692448/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692448/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-21","Revenue and Customs: Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the planned expenditure is on the HM Revenue and Customs identity assurance system planned to replace the Government Gateway service from March 2018.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","64720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692449","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-01","<p>GOV.UK Verify will be the single identification service for individuals. The authentication service that HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is developing to replace the Government Gateway will complement the existing GOV.UK Verify service for business representatives.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC agreed with the Cabinet Office and Department for Work and Pensions to take on responsibility for decommissioning the existing Government Gateway, in line with current contractual arrangements, by March 2018. HMRC and the Government Digital Service are working with government departments to help them find suitable solutions beyond that point.</p><p>The cost of building a replacement Gateway service is commercially sensitive information, and so cannot be provided.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","64720 ; 64722","2017-03-01T15:53:59.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692449/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692449/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692449/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-21","Revenue and Customs: Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which departments plan to use the HM Revenue and Customs identity verification service planned to replace the Government Gateway service from March 2018.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","64721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692450","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-01","<p>GOV.UK Verify will be the single identification service for individuals. The authentication service that HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is developing to replace the Government Gateway will complement the existing GOV.UK Verify service for business representatives.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC agreed with the Cabinet Office and Department for Work and Pensions to take on responsibility for decommissioning the existing Government Gateway, in line with current contractual arrangements, by March 2018. HMRC and the Government Digital Service are working with government departments to help them find suitable solutions beyond that point.</p><p>The cost of building a replacement Gateway service is commercially sensitive information, and so cannot be provided.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","64720 ; 64721","2017-03-01T15:53:59.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692450/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692450/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692450/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-21","Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which transactions are planned to be processed via the (a) new identity verification service planned by HM Revenue and Customs and (b) Government Digital Service platform Verify when the Government Gateway service expires in March 2018.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","64722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692451","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Treasury does not have any premium rate telephone lines and therefore has not accrued any income in this manner in the last five years.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-03-01T14:38:07.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692451/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692451/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692451/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-21","Treasury: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much income has been accrued to his Department from premium rate telephone lines in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","64743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692453","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-01","<p>Since 2009 DCLG has utilised 0303 numbers for inbound calls. At no point since 2009 has DCLG utilised premium rate numbers.</p><p>Additionally each department is asked to provide a yearly report on any premium numbers in use (amongst other numbers). This is published here <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/customer-service-lines-reports" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/customer-service-lines-reports</a>.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-01T17:43:05.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692453/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692453/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692453/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-21","Department for Communities and Local Government: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much income has been accrued to his Department from premium rate telephone lines in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","64737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692454","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-01","<p>Local authorities spend on adult social care is financed through locally raised and retained income such as Council Tax and Business Rates and from centrally distributed revenue streams, such as the Better Care Fund, Revenue Support Grant and specific grants to local authorities and other organisations.</p><p>It is not possible to estimate all the elements of spend that go towards providing care from of each of these central government funding streams.</p><p>Information on adult social care spending by each and all local authorities in England is published on the Department’s website:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing</a></p><p>DCLG has not produced statistics at regional level since 2012, as per Ministerial Statement:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/local-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/local-statistics</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-01T18:08:53.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692454/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692454/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692454/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692454/answer/previousversion/36875","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692454/answer/previousversion/36875",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-21","Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much (a) the Government and (b) local authorities in England spent on adult social care in each year since 2010 by region.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","64733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692455","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-01","<p>Ministers and officials from my department hold regular discussions with HM Treasury. The 2012 reinvigorated Right to Buy scheme increased maximum discounts to realistic levels and, for the first time ever, introduced a requirement that for every additional sale, a new affordable home will be provided nationally. Local authorities are able to keep the receipts from additional Right to Buy sales to fund replacement affordable housing.</p><p>Since the reform of the Housing Revenue Account and the introduction of Self-Financing in April 2012, a proportion of receipts are paid to Treasury, as part of addressing the deficit in the nation’s finances.</p><p>The below figures show the total Right to Buy receipts paid to the Secretary of State since 2012/13.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Receipts Paid to Secretary of Sate</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£127,754,355</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£170,644,428</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£179,746,367</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£222,321,001</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17*</p></td><td><p>£103,602,532</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>£804,068,683</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>*quarters 1&amp;2 only</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-01T17:08:00.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692455/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692455/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692455/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-21","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on the amount that councils are required to pay back in right to buy receipts; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","64700"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692456","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-07","<p>My Department does not publish forecasts for house building. 189,650 new homes were delivered in 2015/16 but we accept we have further to go as a country to build the homes we need.</p><p>The Government’s ambition is to deliver 1 million homes by the end of the Parliament and our Housing White Paper sets out a comprehensive package of reforms to help us to do so.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-07T10:27:17.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692456/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692456/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692456/answer","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692456/answer/previousversion/36899","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692456/answer/previousversion/36899",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-21","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what comparative estimate his Department has made of the number of homes to be built between 2015 and 2020 and the Government's target for the number of homes to be built in that period.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","64796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692458","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government has made no assessment of the potential effect on high streets and local communities of reduced access to ATMs. ATM provision is a matter for HM Treasury.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","64817","2017-03-01T16:59:01.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692458/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692458/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692458/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-21","Small Businesses: Cash Dispensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy on the level of provision for small businesses of ATM access.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","64768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692459","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-28","<p>I intend to, as soon as practicable, carefully consider the proposal for unitary local government submitted by six Dorset councils and announce whether or not I am minded to use my statutory powers to implement that proposal. Once I have announced my initial decision, there will be an opportunity for those interested to submit representations which I shall carefully consider before reaching any final decision.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-28T15:52:54.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692459/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692459/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692459/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692459/answer/previousversion/36900","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692459/answer/previousversion/36900",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-21","Local Government: Dorset","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the closing date is for the submission of (a) objections to the proposal submitted by some Dorset local authorities on 9 February 2017 for local government reorganisation and (b) any alternative or counter-proposals for change to local government structures in Dorset.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","64857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692460","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-01","<p>I have received the letter from the Mayor of Christchurch and will respond imminently.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-01T13:46:38.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692460/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692460/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692460/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692460/answer/previousversion/36903","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692460/answer/previousversion/36903",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-21","Local Government: Christchurch","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to respond to the letter from the Mayor of Christchurch, dated 6 February 2017, on local government reorganisation.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","64858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692461","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-28","<p>As I indicated in my previous answer, it is entirely for the councils concerned to decide whether and if so how they collaborate or work jointly, decisions on which they are accountable to their local electors.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-28T15:54:43.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692461/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692461/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692461/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692461/answer/previousversion/36905","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692461/answer/previousversion/36905",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-21","Unitary Councils","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 9 February 2017 to Question 63312, on unitary councils, how the principles enunciated in that answer apply to councils opposed to a particular proposal for reorganisation but with whom other councils refuse to collaborate or work jointly.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","64859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692463","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-28","<p>It is a matter for the councils concerned to decide their partnership arrangements, subject to any legislation relating to the establishment of those councils and the powers they have.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-28T15:53:59.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692463/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692463/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692463/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692463/answer/previousversion/36907","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692463/answer/previousversion/36907",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-21","Local Government: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 9 February 2017 to Question 63310, on local government: conditions of employment, whether partnership arrangements in place between sovereign councils can be terminated against the will of those sovereign partners.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","64860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692464","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government has made no assessment of the potential effect on high streets and local communities of reduced access to ATMs. ATM provision is a matter for HM Treasury.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","64768","2017-03-01T16:59:00.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692464/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692464/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692464/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-21","Cash Dispensing: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on high streets and local communities of reduced access to ATMs.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","64817"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692466","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-01","<p>In line with the practice of successive administrations details of ministerial discussions are not routinely disclosed.</p><p> </p><p>The Government believes that widespread free access to cash remains extremely important to the day-to-day lives of many consumers in the UK. To this end, the Government is engaging with LINK and its members, including banks and Independent ATM Deployers, to ensure that widespread free access to cash is maintained. The Government is encouraged to hear that LINK’s members have committed to further work to find a solution to the dispute.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is also working closely on the issue with the Payment Systems Regulator (PSR), which was established in 2015 to promote competition, innovation and the needs of end users within payment systems. The PSR is in regular contact with LINK, and is monitoring the situation closely.</p><p> </p><p>The PSR has the power to act if LINK or any of its members act in a way that conflicts with any of its objectives.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","64819","2017-03-01T14:49:38.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692466/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692466/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692466/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-21","Cash Dispensing: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on the effect of changes to the level of access to free ATMs on high streets and local communities.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","64818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692467","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-01","<p>In line with the practice of successive administrations details of ministerial discussions are not routinely disclosed.</p><p> </p><p>The Government believes that widespread free access to cash remains extremely important to the day-to-day lives of many consumers in the UK. To this end, the Government is engaging with LINK and its members, including banks and Independent ATM Deployers, to ensure that widespread free access to cash is maintained. The Government is encouraged to hear that LINK’s members have committed to further work to find a solution to the dispute.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is also working closely on the issue with the Payment Systems Regulator (PSR), which was established in 2015 to promote competition, innovation and the needs of end users within payment systems. The PSR is in regular contact with LINK, and is monitoring the situation closely.</p><p> </p><p>The PSR has the power to act if LINK or any of its members act in a way that conflicts with any of its objectives.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","64818","2017-03-01T14:49:38.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692467/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692467/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692467/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-21","Cash Dispensing","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer and other cabinet colleagues on measures to maintain free ATM provision following reports of a review being undertaken by LINK.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","64819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692468","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-01","<p>The current Troubled Families Programme rolled out across all top tier local authorities in England in April 2015 and has funding committed to 2020.</p><p>This programme is subject to a comprehensive national evaluation, which will report at intervals throughout its lifetime. The Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government has a statutory duty to report annually to Parliament on the progress of the programme. The first report is due to be published by the end of March 2017 and will include details of the programme’s progress so far.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-01T16:24:50.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692468/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692468/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692468/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-21","Families: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what representations he has received on the outcomes of Phase two of the Troubled Families programme since its introduction in 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","64805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692469","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-01","<p>Responsibility for compliance with the building regulations rests with those building new homes. All new homes are subject to supervision by a building control body, which can be a local authority or approved inspector. Building control bodies must take all reasonable steps to ascertain if the building work complies with the relevant requirements of the building regulations and not give a compliance certificate until satisfied that the requirements have been met.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-01T16:58:24.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692469/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692469/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692469/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-21","Housing: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure that all newly built homes comply with building regulations.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","64806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692470","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-24","<p>BBC Worldwide sells advertising for BBC.com, the BBC's main international website. As a commercial subsidiary of the BBC, Worldwide does generate profits which are returned to the BBC, but we have not made any estimates on the revenue from online advertisements - this is a matter for the BBC as editorially and operationally independent.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-24T10:21:56.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692470/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692470/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692470/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-21","BBC: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate she has made of the revenue accrued by the BBC from online advertisements outside the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","64868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692471","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-01","<p>The department has regular discussions with S4C where a range of issues are discussed, including government funding for S4C during the review period.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-01T10:11:35.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692471/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692471/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692471/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-21","S4C","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions she has had with S4C on her Department's contribution to that company's funding over the period of the independent review of S4C.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","64854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692472","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-24","<p>The BBC are required to lay their Annual Account and Report in front of Parliament each year, and this information is available within those accounts and here on the BBC’s website (http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbctrust/our_work/strategy/annualreport/2015_2016.html).</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-24T10:22:28.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692472/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692472/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692472/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-21","BBC","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate she has made of the value of BBC revenue streams excluding the licence fee in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","64866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692473","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-24","<p>As the Secretary of State set out in February 2016, (https://www.gov.uk/government/news/uk-government-protects-funding-for-welsh-broadcaster-s4c--2) the independent review of S4C will look at the funding, governance and remit of S4C. The full scope of the review will be set out in the terms of reference in due course.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-24T10:24:26.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692473/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692473/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692473/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-21","S4C Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when she plans to announce the terms of reference for the independent review of S4C.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","64898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692474","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-02","<p>We intend to issue a consultation during this session of Parliament on making company directors and those in similar positions, accountable for breaches of the Privacy and Electronic Communications Regulations 2003, in relation to direct marketing. The proposed measure would give the Information Commissioner a power to impose Civil Monetary Penalties (CMP) of up to £500,000 on those in positions of responsibility in all forms of corporate entity.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-02T09:16:04.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692474/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692474/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692474/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-21","Data Protection: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, on what date she plans to publish her consultation on legislative proposals on the accountability of named directors of firms responsible for breaches of the Privacy and Electronic Communications Regulations and the related imposition  of fines for such breaches by the Information Commissioner's Office.","false","Biography information for Patricia Gibson","North Ayrshire and Arran","Patricia Gibson","64780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692475","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-01","<p>The BBC, by virtue of its Royal Charter is operationally and editorially independent. It has a duty to deliver duly impartial and accurate news under both its Charter and the Broadcasting Code. The Government has not made any representations to the US Administration on this matter.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-01T10:14:31.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692475/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692475/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692475/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-21","BBC: Political Impartiality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether the Government has made representations to the US Administration related to allegations made by Sebastian Gorka on bias and the impartiality of the BBC on Newsnight on 16 February 2017.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","64782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692476","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-24","<p>The Government welcomed the publication of the BBC's Diversity Strategy in Spring 2016. As the nation's broadcaster, the BBC should be at the forefront of representing diversity both on and off screen. We will follow with interest how the BBC achieves the targets it has set itself.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-24T10:25:25.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692476/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692476/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692476/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-21","BBC: Social Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions she has had with the BBC on social mobility.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","64749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692477","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-24","<p>The £5.8 billion savings target within the Equipment Plan over the next 10 years was agreed with the Cabinet Office and Her Majesty's Treasury during the 2015 Spending Review. It was built into our policies and assumptions, including those relating to the Equipment Plan, at the time.</p><p>As laid out in the National Audit Office's report, the savings will be found from the following areas:</p><p>£1.7 billion from reviews of contracts under the Single Source Contract Regulations;</p><p>£3.3 billion from transformation activities within Defence Equipment and Support;</p><p>£0.8 billion from a number of other sources, including continuing reviews of support projects and test and evaluation expenditure.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-02-24T13:30:36.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692477/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692477/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692477/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-21","Defence Equipment: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the finding of the National Audit Office in its report, entitled The Equipment Plan 2016-2026, published in January 2017, that his Department must generate £5.8 billion of new savings from projects within the Equipment Plan to meet its new commitments; and how his Department plans to make such savings.","false","Biography information for Wayne David","Caerphilly","Wayne David","64755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692478","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Government and the Royal Navy recognise the positive impact Sea Cadets has on young people, helping them to build resilient futures for themselves and their communities. We support the charity with a Grant in Aid payment in the region of £10 million, providing almost half of the cost of delivering the Sea Cadets. We also second personnel to key positions, offering role models that inspire and guide cadets, as well as providing accommodation, equipment, and some training through related facilities on the Ministry of Defence estate. In addition we support the charity's commitment to deliver 10% of the Cadet Expansion Programme, opening 23 units by 2020 helping to make the Sea Cadets Experience accessible to all.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-02-27T16:39:32.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692478/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692478/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692478/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-21","Sea Cadet Corps","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to promote the participation of young people in the Sea Cadets organisation.","false","Biography information for Mims Davies","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","64774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692479","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-24","<p>As with other NATO allies, from time to time we update our approach to ensure we are categorising defence spending fully in accordance with NATO guidelines, seeking to capture all spending contributing to the defence of the United Kingdom.</p><p> </p><p>Military pensions were included in the then NATO Government's return of defence spending for the first time in 2005-06.</p><p> </p><p>War pensions, parts of the Conflict, Stability and Security Fund relating to peacekeeping, and pension payments to retired Ministry of Defence civil servants were first included in 2015-16.</p><p> </p><p>As announced in the July 2015 Budget, elements of the Single Intelligence Account that relate to defence were first included in 2016-17.</p><p> </p><p>NATO sets the criteria for defence spending, and like all NATO members we abide by those criteria.</p><p> </p><p>NATO has confirmed that the UK continues to spend over 2 per cent of GDP on defence.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2017-02-24T13:31:14.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692479/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692479/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692479/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-21","Defence: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, in which financial year (a) war pensions, (b) contributions to UN peacekeeping missions, (c) the Single Intelligence Account and (d) pensions for retired personnel were first included in his Department's reporting to NATO on defence expenditure.","false","Biography information for Wayne David","Caerphilly","Wayne David","64762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692480","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-24","<p>The Ministry of Defence is procuring nine P-8A Poseidon maritime patrol aircraft via a Foreign Military Sale arrangement from the US Government. Under the agreed schedule, the first UK aircraft is due to be delivered in 2019, and the final one is expected in 2021. It is anticipated that the first aircraft will begin to operate from RAF Lossiemouth in 2020.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-02-24T13:31:58.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692480/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692480/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692480/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-21","Maritime Patrol Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he expects the nine Boeing P8 Poseidon aircraft to (a) be delivered and (b) come into service.","false","Biography information for Wayne David","Caerphilly","Wayne David","64763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692481","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-24","<p>Contractual negotiations are still ongoing with a range of commercial companies and the overall costs of the project have yet to be fully finalised.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-02-24T13:32:51.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692481/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692481/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692481/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-21","Maritime Patrol Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his Department's most recent estimate is of the total cost of developing and delivering the UK's maritime patrol capability to 2026; and how much of that cost relates to (a) P8 Poseidon aircraft, (b) wages and training, (c) infrastructure and (d) support at RAF Lossiemouth.","false","Biography information for Wayne David","Caerphilly","Wayne David","64764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692482","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-24","<p>The National Shipbuilding Strategy will be published in spring 2017.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-02-24T13:33:33.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692482/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692482/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692482/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-21","Warships: Shipbuilding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, on what date his Department plan to publish the National Shipbuilding Strategy.","false","Biography information for Wayne David","Caerphilly","Wayne David","64890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692483","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-27","<p>While the Ministry of Defence seeks to respect and uphold human rights throughout its operations, advocacy for human rights activists overseas would not normally be classed as a military task.</p><p>Human rights abroad are the responsibility of the Foreign and Commonwealth Office.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-02-27T16:37:45.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692483/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692483/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692483/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-21","Human Rights: Advocacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps the Government is taking to ensure it provides robust and consistent advocacy on behalf of human rights defenders and in support of civic space in countries where the UK has strategic security and military interests.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","64847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692484","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-24","<p>This information related to Under 25s is not held in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) has a robust and effective resettlement system in place which utilises the highly successful Career Transition Partnership (CTP). All personnel are eligible for the CTP resettlement provision including those medically discharged, or leaving the Armed Forces due to redundancy. These free resettlement services are offered to all ranks and ages of Service personnel and offers flexible support which can be accessed two years before discharge, through to two years post discharge in order to ensure that making the transition to civilian life is as smooth as possible.</p><p> </p><p>The resettlement process includes the provision of housing advice via the Joint Service Housing Advice Office (JSHAO). The past three years JSHAO statistics are given below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Financial Year 2013-14</p></td><td><p>Financial Year 2014-15</p></td><td><p>Financial Year 2015-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Housing Advice Briefs Delivered</p></td><td><p>55</p></td><td><p>56</p></td><td><p>54</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of Army Attendees</p></td><td><p>No figures available</p></td><td><p>547</p></td><td><p>442</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Army Enquiries</p></td><td><p>No figures available</p></td><td><p>258</p></td><td><p>214</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Please note that it is not possible to determine the age of those who attended these briefs. Figures were not broken down by Service prior to Financial Year 2014-15.</p><p> </p><p>The JSHAO provides specific housing information and advice to encourage Service personnel and their families to consider their civilian housing options at any point in their career. This is to ensure that those leaving the Services have an understanding of the civilian housing options available to them and the differing financial implications when occupying civilian housing compared to Service accommodation.</p><p> </p><p>The MOD also works closely with the Department for Communities and Local Government and the Devolved Administrations to ensure Service personnel do not experience disadvantage as a result of their military service when applying for social housing.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-02-24T13:35:03.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692484/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692484/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692484/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-21","Army: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many army leavers aged under 25 have received (a) financial and (b) other assistance with housing resettlement in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","64783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692485","Department for Education","false","2017-02-28","<p>We are currently undertaking evidence gathering and analysis to estimate the potential costs of providing more flexibility for summer born children. This is complex and it is important that we take the time to consider how to implement any possible changes and what new arrangements we might put in place. Any changes we do make will be subject to a full statutory process.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-28T17:22:37.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692485/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692485/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692485/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will estimate the costs of establishing a pilot initiative based across two or more locally authority areas make provision for children who were born prematurely in the summer months to provide flexibility around timing of school entry to summer-born children in order to gather evidence to inform implementation of the School Admissions Code policy changes.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","64815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692486","Department for Education","false","2017-02-27","<p>Our proposals for funding reform will mean that schools and local authority areas will, for the first time, receive a consistent and fair share of the schools budget, so that they can give every child the opportunity to reach their full potential.</p><p> </p><p>For Coventry local authority, the proposals would mean a reduction in schools funding of 2.4%. Coventry South constituency would see a 2.5% reduction in funding for its schools. On funding for pupils with high needs, Coventry local authority would see a significant increase of 10.7%.</p><p> </p><p>To ensure stability for schools, we have proposed substantial protections to limit reductions to any individual school’s budget to manageable levels. No school will face a reduction of more than 1.5% per pupil per year or 3% per pupil overall.</p><p> </p><p>We are also supporting schools to improve their financial health and efficiency. We have produced a collection of tools, information and guidance, which can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/schools-financial-health-and-efficiency" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/schools-financial-health-and-efficiency</a>.</p><p>This collection includes benchmarking tools and workforce planning guidance to support schools to make savings.</p><p> </p><p>Most recently, we published the Schools’ Buying Strategy which will help schools make significant savings, over £1 billion a year by 2019-20, in non-pay and procurement costs.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-27T14:28:23.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692486/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692486/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692486/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","Schools: Coventry South","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the potential effect of the new school funding formula on the level of funding for schools in Coventry South constituency in real terms for each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","64821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692487","Department for Education","false","2017-02-27","<p>The new computing curriculum, introduced from September 2014, introduces pupils to aspects of cyber security from an early age. The curriculum introduces e-safety from Key Stage 1, reflecting the fact that children are increasingly accessing the internet from a young age, and sets out good practice in staying safe online. At secondary, the content develops to reflect the different and escalating risks that young people face as they get older, including how to protect their online privacy and identity. All maintained schools must follow the National Curriculum and academies and free schools may use it as a benchmark. Building on this knowledge, the Computer Science GCSE requires students to develop knowledge and understanding of cyber security including forms of attack, methods of identifying vulnerabilities and ways of protecting systems.</p><p>The Department for Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) recently announced investment of up to £20m in a Cyber Schools Programme, for 14 to 18 year olds, which will develop key skills to help protect businesses against online threats and keep the digital economy secure. The pilot is expected to begin in Autumn 2017 and the programme aims to have at least 5,700 pupils participating by 2021. It is funded under the second National Cyber Security Programme.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-27T17:25:33.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692487/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692487/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692487/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","Cybercrime: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to promote the awareness of cyber security among school-aged children.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","64861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692488","Department for Education","false","2017-03-08","<p>The information that the honourable member requires is not routinely available in Key Stage 5 data. I have asked the statistical head of profession to review the analysis for the information requested by the honourable member. The Department plans to publish this for the first time in a statistical bulletin on Key Stage 5 attainment by characteristics, on 16 March 2017.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","64863 ; 64865","2017-03-08T17:35:53.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692488/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692488/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692488/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","GCE A-level","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 20 February 2017 to Question 63760, on GCE A-level, where the information requested is held.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","64862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692489","Department for Education","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Service Pupil Premium (SPP), which was introduced in April 2011, is additional funding that schools receive to support the educational needs of their pupils who are currently or have recently been Service children in recognition of the specific challenges children that service families face and as part of the commitment to delivering the armed forces covenant. The following table sets out the numbers of pupils attracting the Service Pupil Premium since its introduction:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Pupils attracting SPP</p></td><td><p>45,070</p></td><td><p>52,370</p></td><td><p>57,940</p></td><td><p>64,390</p></td><td><p>68,771</p></td><td><p>73,415</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>We have allocated more than £22.0 million in 2016/17 financial year to support the needs of over 73,000 Service pupils through the SPP.</p><p>Schools are encouraged to identify children eligible for the SPP in their school census returns and the funding is allocated to schools based on these returns.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","64874 ; 64903","2017-03-01T16:08:04.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692489/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692489/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692489/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","Service Pupil Premium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many students who are eligible for the service pupil premium have not received that premium in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","64881"
