"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692491","Department for Education","false","2017-03-08","<p>The information that the honourable member requires is not routinely available in Key Stage 5 data. I have asked the statistical head of profession to review the analysis for the information requested by the honourable member. The Department plans to publish this for the first time in a statistical bulletin on Key Stage 5 attainment by characteristics, on 16 March 2017.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","64862 ; 64865","2017-03-08T17:35:53.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692491/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692491/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692491/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","GCE A-level","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 20 February 2017 to Question 63762, on GCE A-level, where the information requested is held.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","64863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692492","Department for Education","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Service Pupil Premium (SPP), which was introduced in April 2011, is additional funding that schools receive to support the educational needs of their pupils who are currently or have recently been Service children in recognition of the specific challenges children that service families face and as part of the commitment to delivering the armed forces covenant. The following table sets out the numbers of pupils attracting the Service Pupil Premium since its introduction:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Pupils attracting SPP</p></td><td><p>45,070</p></td><td><p>52,370</p></td><td><p>57,940</p></td><td><p>64,390</p></td><td><p>68,771</p></td><td><p>73,415</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>We have allocated more than £22.0 million in 2016/17 financial year to support the needs of over 73,000 Service pupils through the SPP.</p><p>Schools are encouraged to identify children eligible for the SPP in their school census returns and the funding is allocated to schools based on these returns.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","64881 ; 64903","2017-03-01T16:08:04.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692492/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692492/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692492/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","Service Pupil Premium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children have been in receipt of the service pupil premium each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","64874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692493","Department for Education","false","2017-03-06","<p>Our Returners Engagement Programme (REP) pilot provides funding to schools in the North West and South East to support and employ returning maths, physics and languages teachers. Many returning teachers wish to teach on a part-time, flexible or job share basis, and this has shown to be one of the most significant barriers for teachers wanting to return to the profession. Consequently, the pilot is open to schools that are willing to support and employ returning teachers who wish to work on a part-time or flexible basis.</p><p> </p><p>Participating teachers are given a bespoke programme of support to help overcome the barriers that have prevented them from returning to teaching, such as recent classroom experience. They are also eligible for a bursary to contribute towards any increased requirement of childcare provision, travel costs or time off work.</p><p> </p><p>The REP pilot complements the wider national package of support from the dedicated Return to Teaching Adviser service. Through this, returning teachers benefit from</p><p>one to one support, including help in assessing their readiness in returning to teaching, and resources to help secure that readiness.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-06T14:10:41.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692493/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692493/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692493/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","Teachers: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether her Department has a programme to encourage former teachers to return to that profession; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","64894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692494","Department for Education","false","2017-02-27","<p>Our proposals for funding reform will mean that schools will, for the first time, receive a consistent and fair share of the schools budget, so that they can give every child the opportunity to reach their full potential.</p><p> </p><p>For Warrington, the proposals would mean an overall increase in schools funding of 0.6%. On high needs, Warrington would be protected at current funding levels. Warrington North constituency would see a 0.9% increase in funding for its schools.</p><p> </p><p>The current consultation is open until 22 March, and we are keen to hear views from as many schools, governors, local authorities and parents as possible. We will publish our response to the consultation, including details of representations received, in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-27T14:10:39.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692494/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692494/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692494/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","Schools: Warrington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what representations she has received from (a) schools and (b) other bodies on the likely effect of the proposed funding formula on schools in Warrington; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","64908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692495","Department for Education","false","2017-02-27","<p>Our proposals for funding reform will mean that schools and local authority areas will, for the first time, receive a consistent and fair share of the schools budget, so that they can give every child the opportunity to reach their full potential.</p><p> </p><p>For Calderdale, the proposals would mean an increase in schools funding of 1.3%, and an increase of 9.7% for high needs funding.</p><p> </p><p>We are also committed to providing support for schools to improve their financial health and efficiency. We have produced a collection of tools, information and guidance, which can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/schools-financial-health-and-efficiency" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/schools-financial-health-and-efficiency</a>. The collection includes guidance on workforce planning, financial management, benchmarking, and buying for schools.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","64915","2017-02-27T14:35:48.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692495/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692495/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692495/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","Schools: Calderdale","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the effect of changes of the Schools National Funding Formula on funding for schools in Calderdale.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","64914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692496","Department for Education","false","2017-02-27","<p>Our proposals for funding reform will mean that schools and local authority areas will, for the first time, receive a consistent and fair share of the schools budget, so that they can give every child the opportunity to reach their full potential.</p><p> </p><p>For Calderdale, the proposals would mean an increase in schools funding of 1.3%, and an increase of 9.7% for high needs funding.</p><p> </p><p>We are also committed to providing support for schools to improve their financial health and efficiency. We have produced a collection of tools, information and guidance, which can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/schools-financial-health-and-efficiency" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/schools-financial-health-and-efficiency</a>. The collection includes guidance on workforce planning, financial management, benchmarking, and buying for schools.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","64914","2017-02-27T14:35:48.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692496/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692496/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692496/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what advice her Department is providing to schools projected to see reductions in funding under the Schools National Funding Formula on how to balance their budgets.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","64915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692497","Department for Education","false","2017-04-27","<p>In December 2016 the Department confirmed dedicated schools grant (DSG) funding settlements for 2017-18 to local authorities. For all local authorities, funding has been protected in cash terms per pupil. Further details are available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2017-to-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2017-to-2018</a>.</p><p>In 2017-18, individual schools’ funding is decided at a local authority level. The Department allocates funding to each local authority, who then allocate this funding to their schools using their local formulae. The Minimum Funding Guarantee (MFG) ensures that the maximum any individual school can lose is 1.5% per pupil. Local authorities are now finalising and will shortly be confirming their 2017-18 funding to schools. Further information is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/school-revenue-funding-settlement-for-2017-to-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/school-revenue-funding-settlement-for-2017-to-2018</a>.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently consulting on our proposals for a National Funding Formula, which will come into force in 2018-19. The consultation will run until March 22<sup>nd</sup> and is available at <a href="https://consult.education.gov.uk/funding-policy-unit/schools-national-funding-formula2/" target="_blank">https://consult.education.gov.uk/funding-policy-unit/schools-national-funding-formula2/</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-04-27T11:38:37.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692497/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692497/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692497/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much additional funding her Department would require in order to ensure that no school saw a cut in its budget for 2017-18 as part of the Schools National Funding Formula.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","64913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692498","Department for Education","false","2017-02-28","<p>The head count of educational psychologists reported as employed by Norfolk local authority in November each year since 2011 is provided in the table below. Data for 2010 were not provided by the local authority.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>30</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>25</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>23</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>28</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>23</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: School Workforce Census</p><p> </p><p>The Department has approval to advertise for a new training provider in the East of England providing additional 10 training places.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-28T16:13:06.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692498/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692498/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692498/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","Educational Psychology: Norfolk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 17 January 2017 to Question 59084, on Educational Psychology, how many educational psychologists were employed in Norfolk in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","64896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692499","Department for Education","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Service Pupil Premium (SPP), which was introduced in April 2011, is additional funding that schools receive to support the educational needs of their pupils who are currently or have recently been Service children in recognition of the specific challenges children that service families face and as part of the commitment to delivering the armed forces covenant. The following table sets out the numbers of pupils attracting the Service Pupil Premium since its introduction:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Pupils attracting SPP</p></td><td><p>45,070</p></td><td><p>52,370</p></td><td><p>57,940</p></td><td><p>64,390</p></td><td><p>68,771</p></td><td><p>73,415</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>We have allocated more than £22.0 million in 2016/17 financial year to support the needs of over 73,000 Service pupils through the SPP.</p><p>Schools are encouraged to identify children eligible for the SPP in their school census returns and the funding is allocated to schools based on these returns.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","64874 ; 64881","2017-03-01T16:08:04.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692499/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692499/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692499/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","Service Pupil Premium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the take-up of the service pupil premium in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","64903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692500","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-27","<p>Learners undertaking mobility typically enhance their employability, social skills and linguistic skills, and that is why we place particular importance on ensuring learners from disadvantaged backgrounds have the opportunity to undertake mobility. Such learners who successfully apply to participate in the Erasmus+ mobility schemes receive an additional €100 per month abroad as well as the standard contribution to their mobility. Disabled students can also claim any additional costs required to enable their participation, including the cost of an accompanying carer where necessary.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-02-27T14:07:42.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692500/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692500/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692500/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692500/answer/previousversion/36918","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692500/answer/previousversion/36918",,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-21","Erasmus+ Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the benefits of the Erasmus Plus programme for UK learners from disadvantaged backgrounds.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","64930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692501","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-27","<p>Students and apprentices who participate in Erasmus+ mobility typically enhance their employability and their social skills, and staff their professional development; both typically also enhance their linguistic skills.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-02-27T14:09:59.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692501/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692501/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692501/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692501/answer/previousversion/36921","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692501/answer/previousversion/36921",,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-21","Erasmus+ Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the benefits of the Erasmus Plus programme for UK (a) vocational education staff, (b) vocational students and (c) apprentices.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","64933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692502","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Erasmus+ programme is delivered in the UK by the British Council in partnership with Ecorys Ltd., and it is the latter which has responsibility for the vocational education and training sub-programme. Officials in the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy regularly discuss the development of all aspects of the programme with the partnership.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-02-27T14:09:05.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692502/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692502/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692502/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692502/answer/previousversion/36922","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692502/answer/previousversion/36922",,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-21","Erasmus+ Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what contribution his Department has (a) made and (b) plans to make to discussions with the British Council on the future development of the Erasmus Plus programme in the vocational and technical skills sectors.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","64934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692503","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-27","<p>Stakeholder engagement is a central element of our plan to build a national consensus around our negotiating position; we are listening and talking to as many organisations, companies and institutions as possible.</p><p> </p><p>My Rt Hon Friend the Prime Minister has been clear that Britain will remain truly global – the best friend and neighbour to our European partners, but a country that reaches beyond the borders of Europe too.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise the value of international exchange and collaboration in education and training, as part of our vision for the UK as a global nation.</p><p> </p><p>It is too early to speculate on the UK’s future relationship with specific EU programmes, including Erasmus+.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","64932","2017-02-27T14:11:38.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692503/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692503/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692503/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692503/answer/previousversion/36919","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692503/answer/previousversion/36919",,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-21","Erasmus+ Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent discussions he has had with higher education providers and institutions on continued UK participation in the Erasmus Plus programme (a) in the next two years and (b) when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","64931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692504","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-27","<p>Stakeholder engagement is a central element of our plan to build a national consensus around our negotiating position; we are listening and talking to as many organisations, companies and institutions as possible.</p><p> </p><p>My Rt Hon Friend the Prime Minister has been clear that Britain will remain truly global – the best friend and neighbour to our European partners, but a country that reaches beyond the borders of Europe too.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise the value of international exchange and collaboration in education and training, as part of our vision for the UK as a global nation.</p><p> </p><p>It is too early to speculate on the UK’s future relationship with specific EU programmes, including Erasmus+.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","64931","2017-02-27T14:11:38.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692504/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692504/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692504/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692504/answer/previousversion/36920","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692504/answer/previousversion/36920",,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-21","Erasmus+ Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with the British Council on the merits of the continued UK participation in the Erasmus Plus programme (a) in the next two years and (b) after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","64932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692505","Department for Education","false","2017-03-08","<p>The information that the honourable member requires is not routinely available in Key Stage 5 data. I have asked the statistical head of profession to review the analysis for the information requested by the honourable member. The Department plans to publish this for the first time in a statistical bulletin on Key Stage 5 attainment by characteristics, on 16 March 2017.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-08T17:34:01.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692505/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692505/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692505/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","Politics and Government: GCE A-level","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of pupils who took A-levels in government and politics in 2016 were recipients of free school meals during any of their time in secondary school.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","64718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692506","Department for Education","false","2017-03-08","<p>The information that the honourable member requires is not routinely available in Key Stage 5 data. I have asked the statistical head of profession to review the analysis for the information requested by the honourable member. The Department plans to publish this for the first time in a statistical bulletin on Key Stage 5 attainment by characteristics, on 16 March 2017.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-08T17:31:20.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692506/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692506/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692506/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","Politics and Government: GCE A-level","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many pupils of each ethnicity took an A-level in government and politics in 2016.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","64719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692507","Department for Education","false","2017-03-01","<p>We are increasing spending on childcare support to over £6 billion per year by 2019-20. We are investing £1 billion extra every year for the early years entitlements, including over £300 million a year to increase the hourly funding rates for 2, 3 and 4 year olds. The Early Years National Funding Formula (EYNFF) allocates this investment fairly and transparently, so that early years providers, including nurseries, can deliver free childcare on a sustainable and high-quality basis. From April 2017, 80% of local authorities will see increases in their funding rates for 3 and 4 year olds, and all will receive increases in their hourly rates for 2 year olds. The EYNFF allows local authorities to use a quality supplement in their local formulas to recognise workforce qualifications. We have also committed to developing an early years workforce strategy to help employers attract, retain and develop staff to deliver high quality provision.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-03-01T16:47:56.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692507/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692507/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692507/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","Nurseries: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to ensure that nurseries have access to adequate funding to afford well-qualified staff.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","64713"
