"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692514","Department for Education","false","2017-03-08","<p>The information that the honourable member requires is not routinely available in Key Stage 5 data. I have asked the statistical head of profession to review the analysis for the information requested by the honourable member. The Department plans to publish this for the first time in a statistical bulletin on Key Stage 5 attainment by characteristics, on 16 March 2017.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","64792","2017-03-08T17:23:44.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692514/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692514/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692514/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","Arts: GCE A-level","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of students eligible for free school meals have taken (a) art, (b) music and (c) drama A-level in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","64794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692515","Department for Education","false","2017-03-01","<p>Land acquired for free schools, including sites transferred from other public use, remains in public ownership. Free schools are delivering good quality places in areas where these are needed.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-03-01T15:54:20.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692515/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692515/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692515/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","Free Schools: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the total value is of public land transferred to free schools since the establishment of such schools.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","64751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692516","Department for Education","false","2017-03-06","<p>There are currently no new primary school frameworks and therefore we have no plans to issue any guidance.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-03-06T14:30:03.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692516/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692516/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692516/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-21","Primary Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans she has to issue guidance alongside the new primary school framework.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","64752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692517","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs has accrued no income from premium rate telephone lines in the last five years.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-27T12:36:23.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692517/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692517/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692517/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-21","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much income has been accrued to her Department from premium rate telephone lines in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","64738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692518","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-28","<p>Objectives and actions to protect and improve chalk streams are included in England’s river basin management plans. These plans provide the framework setting out how our rivers will improve over the next 6 years from investment and activity across the sectors.</p><p> </p><p>Working with Natural England, the Environment Agency carries out monitoring and works with water companies and other stakeholders where actions are identified to protect and improve our water environment including chalk streams.</p><p> </p><p>The Agency has changed 63 abstraction licences relating to 15 chalk streams across England, which has returned 16 million cubic metres per year of water back to chalk streams. Further, as a result of River Restoration Strategies and Site Improvement Plans being implemented on Sites of Special Scientific Interest chalk streams, 70 kilometres of priority chalk stream have been improved since 2011. Water company investment on phosphate removal at sewage treatment works across England will also benefit chalk rivers.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-02-28T12:35:48.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692518/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692518/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692518/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-21","Rivers: Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of environmental protections for chalk streams.","false","Biography information for Mims Davies","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","64775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692519","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Environment Agency has worked closely with the Angling Trust to develop the Angling Alert system, enabling important messages about illegal fishing and fisheries enforcement to be shared with registered anglers. The system and its costs are organised through the National Angling Strategic Service, which is provided by the Angling Trust for the Environment Agency. All work associated with the Angling Alert system is funded by rod licence income.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-01T12:57:07.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692519/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692519/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692519/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-21","Angling Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what budget and staffing resources have been allocated by her Department and its agencies to Angling Trust Alert (ATA); what meetings officials of her Department and its agencies have had with ATA in the last three years; and what agreements have been reached at each of those meetings.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","64765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692520","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-27","<p>We recently announced that we will modernise the licensing scheme for dog breeding and selling to improve the welfare of dogs, including requiring anyone breeding and selling three or more puppies in a twelve month period to hold a licence; prohibiting the sale of puppies under eight weeks’ of age; imposing tougher animal welfare standards on licensed dog breeders and sellers; and requiring all licensed sellers to include their licence number when advertising.</p><p> </p><p>We aim to have the new regulations in place next year.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-27T12:42:28.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692520/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692520/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692520/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-21","Dogs: Animal Breeding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to tackle animal cruelty in puppy farms.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","64919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692521","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-02","<p>Anyone may bring forward a prosecution under the Animal Welfare Act 2006 and the Government does not intend to change that position.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In the light of public criticisms of its role, the RSPCA set up the Wooler Review, which made 33 recommendations which the RSPCA have already assessed and considered for action. We believe that the RSPCA should be given the opportunity to implement the recommendations of the Wooler Review and demonstrate its commitment to responding to the concerns that have been raised.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-02T14:22:09.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692521/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692521/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692521/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-21","RSPCA: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether she plans to remove the right of the RSPCA to prosecute cases of animal cruelty.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","64920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692522","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Government is considering this issue very carefully.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-27T13:12:57.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692522/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692522/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692522/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-21","Fisheries: Treaties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if the Government will consider invoking Articles 15 and 11 of the 1964 London Fisheries Convention after triggering Article 50 of the Lisbon Treaty.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","64928"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692523","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>Despite the signing of the Libyan Political Agreement (LPA) in December 2015, the political and security situation in Libya remains fragile. A number of players continue to obstruct full implementation of the LPA, and the Government of National Accord has still not been approved by the House of Representatives. The UK remains committed to the LPA and is supportive of current efforts to amend it in order to secure support from those Libyans who have hitherto opposed it. An inclusive government which brings together Libyans from across the country is the best way to restore unity, rebuild the economy and tackle the threats posed by Daesh and illegal migration.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-01T15:56:48.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692523/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692523/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692523/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Libya: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the political stability of Libya; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","64922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692524","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>We have not received any representations on legislation of gay marriage in the overseas territories since the Hon. Member for Tottenham (Mr Lammy) asked questions 52680 and 52682 in November 2016.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-03-01T17:09:44.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692524/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692524/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692524/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","British Overseas Territories: Marriage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has received recent representations from (a) parliamentarians and (b) the public on the legalisation of gay marriage in the overseas territories.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","64904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692525","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>We are concerned by the increased anti-homosexual rhetoric and steadily deteriorating LGBT environment in Tanzania. Our High Commission in Dar es Salaam has been monitoring the situation closely and will meet with the Minister of Health in the near future to raise our concerns.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-01T15:54:15.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692525/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692525/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692525/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Tanzania: Homosexuality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has made representations to his Tanzanian counterpart on that Government's proposals to publish lists of homosexuals.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","64921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692526","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>​I issued a statement on 7 February condemning the land regularisation law. We are gravely concerned by the law, which will retroactively legalise 53 outposts and pave the way for significant growth in settlements deep in the West Bank, threatening the viability of the two-state solution. The Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead (Mrs May) and the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson) both expressed concerns about settlement activity when they met Prime Minister Netanyahu in London on Monday 6 February.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-01T14:56:34.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692526/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692526/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692526/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","West Bank: Israeli Settlements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will discuss with his Israeli counterparts the effect of the Land Regularisation Bill recently passed by the Israeli Knesset on the number of Israeli settlements on the West Bank.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","64925"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692527","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>We are concerned by the increased anti-homosexual rhetoric and steadily deteriorating LGBT environment in Tanzania. Our High Commission in Dar es Salaam has been monitoring the situation closely; officials are also part of an LGBT taskforce, which regularly meets with advocacy groups, including Stonewall and Human Rights Watch, to support LGBT rights in Tanzania.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-01T15:52:20.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692527/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692527/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692527/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Tanzania: LGBT People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of LGBT rights in Tanzania.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","64906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692528","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>​The Government has no plans to amend the UN Security Council Resolution governing the freezing of Libyan assets in the UK. There is no legal basis upon which the UK could seize frozen assets or withhold Libyan assets once the relevant Libyan entities are delisted and the assets unfrozen. Once these assets are released they belong to the people of Libya and by law have to be returned for their benefit.</p><p>We have however made clear to the Libyan authorities that resolution of legacy issues remains a priority for us. I raised the issue of compensation in my meetings with Prime Minister Serraj and Deputy Prime Minister Maiteq during the London Ministerial on 31 October 2016. We will continue to encourage the Libyan authorities to engage with UK victims, and their legal representatives, seeking redress, including those seeking compensation.</p><p>The Government position remains that it is not able to negotiate with the Libyan government on individual compensation claims, as these are not government-to-government claims. These are private matters best pursued directly with the Libyan authorities. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office provides facilitation support to victims, their representatives and campaign groups, where it has been requested and is appropriate.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-01T16:22:41.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692528/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692528/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692528/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Libya: Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when he plans to open negotiations with the Libyan Government on that country's frozen assets and provision for UK victims of Libyan-sponsored terrorism.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","64879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692529","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>​The UK has regularly supported pro-peace projects run by Israeli Non-Governmental Organisations. We are currently supporting a project to empower young Israeli religious leaders to strengthen support for peace in their communities. The Department for International Development is also developing a programme of support for people-to-people projects in Israel and the Occupied Palestinian Territories, which will help Israelis and Palestinians work together to achieve tangible improvements in their lives and build understanding.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-02-24T16:07:50.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692529/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692529/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692529/answer","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692529/answer/previousversion/36930","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692529/answer/previousversion/36930",,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Israel: Peace","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what diplomatic and development-related steps his Department is taking to support peace groups in Israel.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","64916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692530","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>The next Overseas Territories Joint Ministerial Council is due to be held in November 2017. The agenda has not yet been agreed.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-03-01T17:05:12.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692530/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692530/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692530/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Overseas Territories Joint Ministerial Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when the next Overseas Territories Joint Ministerial Council is due to take place; and what is on the agenda for that meeting.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","64870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692531","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>We recognise the Republic of Cyprus's sovereign rights to exploit its natural resources. It remains our position that such resources should be exploited for the benefit of all the communities in Cyprus. Ultimately, the best way of enabling that is through a comprehensive settlement to end the division of the island.</p><p>We have discussed with the Government of Cyprus a number of issues related to the development of its hydrocarbon reserves, ranging from support for UK companies bidding for exploration licences or offering other specialist services, to the sharing of expertise in environmental safety, energy security and other areas.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-03-01T17:15:55.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692531/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692531/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692531/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Cyprus: Fossil Fuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions his Department has had with the Government of Cyprus on assistance with the exploitation of gas and oil off the Cyprus coastline.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692532","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Government is committed to supporting Nigeria in the fight against Boko Haram. We are providing a substantial package of military, intelligence and development support including training and advice for the Nigerian armed forces. To date over 22,500 Nigerian military personnel have received UK training, a significant number of whom have been deployed on counter-insurgency operations in North-East Nigeria. With France and the US, we are supporting a Nigerian intelligence analysis and planning cell focused on the North East and based in Abuja. In addition we have provided £5 million to support the Multinational Joint Task Force, a regional taskforce against Boko Haram.</p><p>In 2014, UK surveillance aircraft were deployed to Nigeria to assist the authorities for a limited period. We have not provided any aircraft or helicopter support to the Nigerian military since then.</p><p>Tackling Boko Haram requires a comprehensive approach that also addresses the political, economic and development problems in north east Nigeria. The Department for International Development's (DFID) portfolio for the North East includes programming in health, education, governance, social development and economic growth. In addition, through DFID, the UK is the second largest donor to the humanitarian crisis in Nigeria and Lake Chad. In September 2016 we pledged a further £80m of aid. This is on top of almost £90m of UK humanitarian aid already that is already being delivered in the region.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-01T15:50:28.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692532/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692532/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692532/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Nigeria: Boko Haram","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assistance the Government is giving to the Government of Nigeria to help tackle the activities of Boko Haram; and whether that assistance includes the provision of aircraft or helicopter support.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64841"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692533","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>​I opened the UK-China Human Rights Dialogue in London on 27 October 2016, where the UK raised concerns about allegations of organ harvesting.</p><p>The World Health Organisation (WHO) collates global data on organ donations and works with China on this issue. Officials from our Embassy in Beijing met representatives of the WHO earlier this year. Their view was that China was implementing an ethical, voluntary organ transplant system in accordance with international standards, although they did have concerns about overall transparency.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-03-01T16:59:59.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692533/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692533/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692533/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","China: Organs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to the Government of China on organ harvesting in that country; and what the outcome of those representations has been.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692534","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>​The Foreign Secretary met all the Leaders of the Overseas Territories in November 2016. All travel is continually reviewed and future visits will be announced in the usual way.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-03-01T17:07:53.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692534/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692534/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692534/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","British Overseas Territories: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he plans to visit any of the overseas territories in the next 12 months.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","64882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692535","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>​We have not raised this issue with the Palestinian Authority (PA), as the PA, at this present time, has no control over the Gaza Strip. The increasing use of the death penalty in Gaza is a worrying trend. The UK maintains a no contact policy with the de facto authority in Gaza, Hamas.</p><p>The local EU Heads of Mission issued a statement on 21 February condemning the use of the death penalty in this case and calling on the de facto authorities in Gaza to refrain from carrying out any executions in line with the PA’s moratorium on executions.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-01T14:53:50.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692535/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692535/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692535/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Palestinians: Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations his Department has made to the Palestinian Authority on death sentences imposed on Palestinians for the alleged collaboration with the Israeli Authorities.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","64883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692536","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>The British Government's 2015 manifesto included a commitment to stand up for the rule of law and human rights in Zimbabwe. Ahead of the 2018 elections, it is essential that reforms are made to the Zimbabwean electoral system, including strengthening the independence of the Zimbabwe Electoral Commission and removal of unconstitutional legislation which restricts democratic activity and human rights. With the Department for International Development, the FCO is working through a multi-donor programme to improve access to justice, media and information freedom and to improve the electoral environment in advance of the 2018 elections. Officials remain in close contact with international partners, including the UN, to co-ordinate support in the run up to the 2018 elections.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-01T15:44:40.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692536/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692536/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692536/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Zimbabwe: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to help ensure free and fair elections in Zimbabwe; and what discussions his Department has had with the UN on international action in that area.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692537","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>The UK welcomes the release, on 4 August 2016, by Joint Incidents Assessment Team (JIAT) of the outcome of eight investigations into incidents of alleged breaches of international humanitarian law in Yemen. It is important that credible allegations of violations of international humanitarian law are investigated and the Saudi-led Coalition has committed to doing this. We regularly press, including at senior levels, the need for the Saudi-led Coalition to conduct thorough and conclusive investigations into reports of alleged violations of international humanitarian law.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-01T16:24:31.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692537/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692537/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692537/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 13 January 2017 to Question 58527, what assessment he has made of the validity of the findings of the Saudi-led Coalition's Joint Incident Assessment Team's Investigations of eight airstrikes, published on 4 August 2016.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","64848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692538","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>We are deeply concerned at the ongoing substantial fighting and displacement in South Sudan, particularly in such hotspots as Greater Upper Nile, where it is a direct cause of the ongoing famine, and the Equatorias. An estimated 80,000 people have been forced out of their homes due to insecurity in the last month alone, and there are still widespread reports of grave human rights abuses and violations committed by both sides. The UK continues to pursue every opportunity to call on all parties in the conflict in South Sudan to cease hostilities and engage in a genuine dialogue. We are working closely with the UN, African Union, the region and other partners to facilitate an inclusive dialogue in an effort to revive the peace process.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-02-24T16:04:07.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692538/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692538/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692538/answer","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692538/answer/previousversion/36929","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692538/answer/previousversion/36929",,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","South Sudan: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the security situation in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","64823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692539","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>The US Embassy has confirmed that all international travellers must obtain an appropriate visa for the purpose of travel unless they qualify for entry under the Visa Waiver Program.</p><p>The US authorities do not comment on individual cases but have confirmed that the incident is not related to President Trump's 27th January Executive Order, which has been suspended. We will continue to offer assistance to any British nationals that require it, but we cannot influence US immigration decisions.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","64825","2017-02-24T14:15:01.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692539/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692539/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692539/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Juhel Miah","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has discussed the case of Mr Juhel Miah, a British National who was removed from a flight from Reykjavik to New York on 16 February 2017, with his (a) Icelandic and (b) American counterparts.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","64824"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692540","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>The US Embassy has confirmed that all international travellers must obtain an appropriate visa for the purpose of travel unless they qualify for entry under the Visa Waiver Program.</p><p>The US authorities do not comment on individual cases but have confirmed that the incident is not related to President Trump's 27th January Executive Order, which has been suspended. We will continue to offer assistance to any British nationals that require it, but we cannot influence US immigration decisions.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","64824","2017-02-24T14:15:01.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692540/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692540/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692540/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Juhel Miah","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, for what reason Mr Juhel Miah was removed from a flight from Reykjavik to New York on 16 February 2017.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","64825"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692541","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>Government ministers and officials have regular discussions with NATO Allies on the process of Georgian integration with NATO, including at last week’s NATO Defence Ministerial and NATO-Georgia Commission meeting. The Substantial NATO-Georgia Package (SNGP) agreed at the NATO Summit in Wales (2014) supports Georgia’s work to strengthen its institutions and interoperability with NATO. At the NATO Summit in Warsaw in July 2016, Allies reaffirmed their commitment that Georgia would become a member of NATO and expanded and deepened areas of cooperation under the SNGP.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-03-01T16:29:28.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692541/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692541/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692541/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Georgia: NATO","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterparts in (a) the US and (b) other NATO member states on a potential NATO Membership Action Plan for Georgia.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","64816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692542","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>We welcome Georgia’s commitment to the non-use of force. We continue to believe that a clear commitment to the non-use of force by all parties to the conflicts, including Russia, is essential to enhance regional security and consolidate stability in Georgia. This is particularly important in light of the continued Russian military presence and infrastructure reinforcements in the breakaway regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia, which violate Georgia’s sovereignty and territorial integrity.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-03-01T16:25:32.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692542/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692542/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692542/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Georgia: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what his policy is on the draft statement on non-use force produced by the co-chairs of the Geneva International Discussions; and what assessment he has made of the prospects for an agreement on that draft among all parties to the discussions.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","64813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692543","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-28","<p>I and my Ministerial colleagues have regular discussions with our Georgian counterparts and both sides have agreed that we look forward to maintaining the closest diplomatic and economic ties following the UK’s exit from the European Union. The UK’s commitment to Georgia as a valuable international security partner and regional democratic role model is unwavering. The Minister of State for Europe and the Americas, my Right Hon. Friend the Member for Rutland and Melton (Sir Alan Duncan), visited Tbilisi in November 2016 as head of the UK delegation for the annual bilateral Wardrop Dialogue, which takes place at Ministerial and official level between our two countries. The Wardrop Dialogue was upgraded to strategic level in 2016, a marker of our continued commitment to Georgia. We are already the world’s second biggest investor in Georgia and over January-September 2016 bilateral trade was at £100 million, a 50 per cent increase compared to the same period in 2015.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-02-28T16:45:25.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692543/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692543/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692543/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Georgia: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Georgian counterpart on maintaining diplomatic and economic ties between the UK and Georgia after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","64814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692544","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-28","<p>13 of the 208 staff at the European Union Monitoring Mission (EUMM) in Georgia are British – three are funded by the EU and 10 are funded by the British Government. The EUMM, deployed in the wake of the August 2008 Georgian-Russian war to monitor the implementation of the Peace Agreements of 1 August and 8 September, is an important stabilising factor and trusted independent arbiter in any cross boundary issues. The UK's continued political and practical support to the EUMM is a clear demonstration of UK commitment to Georgia's territorial integrity and sovereignty. As the Minister of State for Europe and the Americas, my right hon. Friend the Member for Rutland and Melton (Sir Alan Duncan), said in his Explanatory Memorandum to the European Scrutiny Committee of December 2016, we assess that the mission continues to perform valuable work in the field, in challenging circumstances, and it remains the only international mission on the ground monitoring implementation of the 2008 peace agreements.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-02-28T16:24:03.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692544/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692544/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692544/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Georgia: Peacekeeping Operations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what support the Government is providing to the EU Monitoring Mission in Georgia; and what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the work of that mission.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","64809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692545","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>​We continue to monitor the security situation in South Ossetia and Abkhazia, noting with concern recent developments such as increased deployments of Russian military and heavy weaponry<em>, </em>increasingly limited access for international organisations and Non-governmental Organisation further restrictions for civilians seeking to cross the Administrative Boundary Lines for work or education, denial of access to education in children's first language in the Gali region of Abkhazia, and de facto 'borders' reinforced with razor wire. We actively support efforts in multilateral fora to highlight these concerns and encourage all parties to the conflicts to work towards resolution.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-03-01T16:09:37.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692545/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692545/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692545/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Georgia: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the security situation in the South Ossetia and Abkhazia regions of Georgia.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","64810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692546","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>​The 39th round of the Geneva International Discussions is scheduled for 28-29 March 2017. The British Government, in line with all other EU member states, has a clear policy of non-recognition of Abkhazia and South Ossetia's claims to independence, and recognises Georgia's territorial integrity and its sovereignty over these two regions. We encourage all parties to the Geneva International Discussions to work towards resolution of the conflicts and an improved humanitarian situation for the conflict-affected populations.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-03-01T16:16:17.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692546/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692546/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692546/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Georgia: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when he expects the next round of the Geneva International Discussions to be held; and what the Government's priorities will be for those discussions.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","64811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692547","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>​The British Government is not directly represented at the Geneva International Discussions (GID). The UK is a member of all three international organisations acting as co-chairs. We continue to support the GID dialogue process as a platform for all parties to the conflict to discuss both security issues and the humanitarian needs of the conflict-affected populations.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-03-01T16:22:00.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692547/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692547/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692547/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Georgia: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, who represented the Government at the 38th round of the Geneva International Discussions in December 2016; and what assessment the Government has made of the outcome of those discussions.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","64812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692548","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-02-24","<p>I refer the honourable Member to the letter sent to her office on 24 February, and reiterate the apologies in that letter for the delay related to the changes in Ministry of Government.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-02-24T12:33:32.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692548/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692548/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692548/answer",,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-02-21","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, when he plans to respond to the letter of 7 June 2016 relating to the EU referendum that was previously transferred to the Department for Exiting the European Union following that Department's refusal to reply to the correspondence.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","64789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692549","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>We are aware of reports of the expulsion of 32 South Korean missionaries from the Yanji region of China by the Chinese authorities.</p><p>We have no plans to raise these specific cases with the Chinese Government, as this is a matter for the South Korean Government.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-02-24T13:18:27.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692549/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692549/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692549/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","China: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to the Chinese Government on the recent expulsion of missionaries from the Chinese border region with North Korea.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","64800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692550","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>We were deeply concerned to hear about the murder of Pastor Jean-Paul Sankagui; faith leaders play an important role in bringing reconciliation, diffusing tensions and promoting social cohesion in the Central African Republic (CAR).</p><p>We remain concerned by the serious violence which has continued throughout CAR since September 2016, leaving thousands displaced and hundreds killed. Our non-resident Ambassador met President Touadera in Bangui earlier this month where he raised the security situation and the destabilising effect armed groups are having on the country.</p><p>We will continue to raise our concerns about the security situation, including incidences such as the murder of Pastor Sankagui, in our contacts with the CAR Government. We will also continue to work with and through our international partners, such as the UN peacekeeping mission (MINUSCA) and the EU Training Mission (EUFOR CAR), to bring stability to CAR.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-02-24T16:01:08.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692550/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692550/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692550/answer","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692550/answer/previousversion/36928","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692550/answer/previousversion/36928",,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-21","Central African Republic: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to the Government of the Central African Republic on the recent murder of a pastor with the Eglise du Christ en Centrafrique and destruction of his church's property.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","64801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692551","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>Under European Union Regulations, other European Economic Area (EEA) countries and Switzerland reimburse the United Kingdom for the cost of the National Health Service providing treatment to people they are responsible for under EU law, including UK nationals insured in another EEA country or Switzerland. In the same way, the UK Government reimburses other EEA countries and Switzerland for the cost of providing treatment to people we are responsible for under EU law, irrespective of nationality.</p><p> </p><p>All EEA counties, including the UK, have a legal obligation to pay agreed claims relating to healthcare treatment provided. Once both sides are satisfied that such claims are accurate, they are paid in full.</p><p> </p><p>As such, the Secretary of State does not need to make formal representations to other Member States for payments.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-01T15:08:11.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692551/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692551/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692551/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Health Services: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent representations he has made to the governments of other EEA countries on funds owed to the NHS.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","64750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692552","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Department does not use premium rate telephones lines where any accruals are made by the Department, and have not done so over the past five years.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-01T10:45:52.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692552/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692552/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692552/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Department of Health: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much income has been accrued to his Department from premium rate telephone lines in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","64739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692553","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>Information on the Net Ingredient Cost (NIC), number of prescription items and NIC per prescription item is provided below. NIC is the basic cost of a drug, and does not take account of discounts, dispensing fees or prescription charges income.</p><p> </p><p>Fucithalmic is the branded version of the drug fusidic acid. Information is provided for fusidic acid viscous eye drops 1%, and is shown for the brand Fucithalmic and the non-branded fusidic acid.</p><p> </p><p>The brand was discontinued in August 2014 according to information in the Dictionary of Medicines and Devices and replaced by a generic version.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>NIC, number of prescription items and NIC per item for branded, non-branded and total fusidic acid eye drops 1%, written in the United Kingdom and dispensed in the community in England for years 2011 to 2015.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="3"><p>Fucithalmic Viscous Eye Drops 1%</p></td><td colspan="3"><p>Fusidic Acid Viscous Eye Drops 1%</p></td><td colspan="3"><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>NIC (£000s)</p></td><td><p>Items (000s)</p></td><td><p>NIC per item (£)</p></td><td><p>NIC (£000s)</p></td><td><p>Items (000s)</p></td><td><p>NIC per item (£)</p></td><td><p>NIC (£000s)</p></td><td><p>Items (000s)</p></td><td><p>NIC per item (£)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>1,186.3</p></td><td><p>556.1</p></td><td><p>2.13</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>1,186.3</p></td><td><p>556.1</p></td><td><p>2.13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>1,252.1</p></td><td><p>586.1</p></td><td><p>2.14</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>1,252.1</p></td><td><p>586.1</p></td><td><p>2.14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>1,316.8</p></td><td><p>561.9</p></td><td><p>2.34</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>1,316.8</p></td><td><p>561.9</p></td><td><p>2.34</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>738.2</p></td><td><p>256.6</p></td><td><p>2.88</p></td><td><p>886.2</p></td><td><p>148.8</p></td><td><p>5.96</p></td><td><p>1,624.4</p></td><td><p>405.4</p></td><td><p>4.01</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>57.1</p></td><td><p>19.3</p></td><td><p>2.95</p></td><td><p>6,016.5</p></td><td><p>313.4</p></td><td><p>19.20</p></td><td><p>6,073.5</p></td><td><p>332.8</p></td><td><p>18.25</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source:</em> Prescription Cost Analysis provided by NHS Digital.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Health Service Medical Supplies (Costs) Bill will strengthen the Secretary of State’s existing powers to control the cost of unbranded generic medicines by enabling the Secretary of State to set the price of a medicine when the manufacturer is in the voluntary pricing scheme but the medicine is not covered by that scheme. The Bill will also provide a statutory footing for current voluntary arrangements to obtain information on more products and from more companies, which will inform reimbursement arrangements for community pharmacies.</p><p> </p><p>The Competition and Markets Authority has a number of live investigations into potential excessive prices of unbranded generic medicines.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-01T14:35:00.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692553/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692553/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692553/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Eye Drops: Prescriptions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the cost to the public purse has been of an individual prescription of Fucithalmic viscous eye drops in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","64698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692554","Department of Health","false","2017-02-24","<p>The tenure of the 217 vacant properties held by NHS Property Services is as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Tenure</p></td><td><p>Number of Properties</p></td><td><p>Proportion (%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Freehold and long leasehold</p></td><td><p>146</p></td><td><p>67</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Leasehold</p></td><td><p>69</p></td><td><p>32</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other formal tenure arrangements</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>0.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>0.5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The 217 properties constitute 6.9% of the total number in the NHS Property Services portfolio and in calculating 217 as the number of vacant properties, the following assumptions were made:</p><p> </p><p>- ‘Property’ refers to a physical building or structure rather than a site or legal holding (i.e. some facilities sit on several land-holdings); and</p><p>- Vacant Properties are defined as those properties where at least 90% of the Net Internal Area is classed as vacant.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-02-24T10:38:50.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692554/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692554/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692554/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","NHS: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 9 February 2017 to Question 63167, what proportion of the 217 vacant properties are (a) freehold, (b) leasehold, (c) other formal tenure agreements and (d) other.","true","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","64731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692555","Department of Health","false","2017-02-24","<p>National Health Service mental health expenditure is not collected by region.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-02-24T10:15:25.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692555/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692555/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692555/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Mental Health Services: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much the NHS and its agencies spent on mental health services in each year since 2010 by region.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","64732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692556","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>NHS Blood and Transplant (NHSBT) works to ensure that the right amount of blood is collected to meet patient need in England, including more complex needs for specific blood groups. It runs a number of campaigns throughout the year to raise awareness of blood donation and to encourage people to register as blood donors.</p><p> </p><p>NHSBT also engages with donors who have rare blood types including working with local charities, to engage people from these communities in blood and organ donation. To meet the demand for specific blood groups, NHSBT is recruiting increasing numbers of O negative blood donors, A negative platelet donors and more donors from black-African, black-Caribbean, Asian and mixed race heritage.</p><p> </p><p>For example, it recently partnered with MOBO on a campaign to encourage people from black and South Asian communities to become blood donors and has launched a toolkit to assist Members of Parliament who are seeking to increase the number of people from these communities who register as blood and organ donors in their constituencies, which is accessible at:</p><p><a href="http://www.bit.do/MPToolkit" target="_blank">www.bit.do/MPToolkit</a></p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-01T11:12:29.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692556/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692556/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692556/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Blood: Donors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to increase the rate of blood donation.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","64703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692557","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>NHS Blood and Transplant (NHSBT) is the organ donor organisation for the United Kingdom and is responsible for promoting organ donation and the matching and allocating of donated organs. Transplant centres for every organ do not exist in each of the devolved nations meaning patients need to travel to other areas of the UK for transplant. For this reason NHSBT does not report on waiting times in each of the devolved nations. Average waiting times are available by transplant centre in NHSBT’s Annual Report. An archive of these reports can be found at:</p><p><a href="http://www.odt.nhs.uk/uk-transplant-registry/annual-activity-report/" target="_blank">www.odt.nhs.uk/uk-transplant-registry/annual-activity-report/</a></p><p> </p><p>The number of people who died while on waiting lists for organ donation is also given in the Annual Report.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","64706","2017-03-01T11:22:05.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692557/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692557/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692557/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Kidneys: Transplant Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people on the organ transplant register died while waiting for a donated kidney in the last financial year.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","64704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692558","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>We seek to ensure as many people as possible get transplants in a timely fashion.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-01T11:17:17.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692558/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692558/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692558/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Kidneys: Transplant Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what comparative assessment he has made of the potential effect on the NHS budget of increasing the number of people receiving kidney transplants to reduce the average waiting time on the transplant register and providing long-term dialysis for the same number of people.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","64705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692559","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>NHS Blood and Transplant (NHSBT) is the organ donor organisation for the United Kingdom and is responsible for promoting organ donation and the matching and allocating of donated organs. Transplant centres for every organ do not exist in each of the devolved nations meaning patients need to travel to other areas of the UK for transplant. For this reason NHSBT does not report on waiting times in each of the devolved nations. Average waiting times are available by transplant centre in NHSBT’s Annual Report. An archive of these reports can be found at:</p><p><a href="http://www.odt.nhs.uk/uk-transplant-registry/annual-activity-report/" target="_blank">www.odt.nhs.uk/uk-transplant-registry/annual-activity-report/</a></p><p> </p><p>The number of people who died while on waiting lists for organ donation is also given in the Annual Report.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","64704","2017-03-01T11:22:05.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692559/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692559/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692559/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Transplant Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he has made a comparative assessment of the average waiting time on the organ transplant register in (a) England and (b) each of the other devolved nations.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","64706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692560","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>There are no plans to collect such data centrally.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-01T15:07:06.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692560/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692560/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692560/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Ambulance Services: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answers of 11 January 2017 and 24 January 2017 to Questions 58829 and 59987, if he will require Ambulance Service NHS Trusts to collect and hold centrally data on the usage of private ambulances and their crews provided by (a) St John's Ambulance, (b) Jigsaw Medical Services and (c) other providers.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","64802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692561","Department of Health","false","2017-02-24","<p>The National Health Service is committed to providing high quality care and will always put the interests of patients first when decisions are made about service transfers.</p><p> </p><p>Following the publication of the Care Quality Commission’s report of Bridgewater Community Healthcare Foundation Trust, NHS Improvement took the decision to pause temporarily the ongoing transaction of services from Liverpool Community Health NHS Trust to Bridgewater Community Healthcare NHS Trust. This pause was deemed appropriate as it has allowed time to seek assurance that the proposals are the best option for local patients and residents. An overall rating of ‘requires improvement’ would not, in itself, prevent a transaction taking place.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-02-24T10:31:05.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692561/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692561/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692561/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Community Health Services: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what duty of care he has for residents and NHS patients in Liverpool following the Capsticks report and while the Kirkup Review is taking place before allowing local community services to be taken over by Bridgewater NHS Trust whose Care Quality Commission inspection report released on 6 February 2017 rates that Trust as requiring improvement.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","64786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692562","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>We are not able to report the number of families of newborn babies nationally that did not receive a mandated health visitor antenatal visit in the last year. Although Public Health England (PHE) holds data on the number of mothers who received an antenatal visit at or after 28 weeks this cannot be linked to the quarterly birth data available. As a result the number of families who did not receive an antenatal visit cannot be calculated.</p><p> </p><p>Data are as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Number of families nationally</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Which did not receive a baby review in the last year (2015/16)</p></td><td><p>15,609</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Which did not receive a six to eight week assessment in the last year</p></td><td><p>119,412</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Which did not receive a one-year assessment in the last year</p></td><td><p>119,107</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Which did not receive a two to two-and-a-half year review in the last year</p></td><td><p>160,656</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The most recent data (above) covers the period 1 October 2015 to 30 September 2016 inclusive. The source of this data is the Health Visitor Service Delivery Metrics, which have been collected from local authorities on a voluntary basis and validated by PHE.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-01T17:02:19.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692562/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692562/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692562/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Maternity Services: Health Visitors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many families of newborn babies did not receive a mandated health visitor antenatal visit in the last year; and how many families did not receive a (a) new baby review, (b) 6 to 8 week assessment, (c) one-year assessment and (e) two to two-and-a-half year review.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","64884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692563","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>Vacuum assisted biopsy is an established diagnostic tool for breast problems already available in the National Health Service. The technique is also used to remove benign breast lumps. However, further research into the use of vacuum assisted biopsy to treat breast cancer is required before it is used more widely.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-01T10:42:50.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692563/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692563/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692563/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Breast Cancer: Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the timetable is for surgery to vacuum cancerous breast tumours to be available on the NHS.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692564","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>Falls and falls-related injuries such as fractures are a common and serious health issue faced by older people in England.</p><p> </p><p>Public Health England (PHE), in partnership with Saga and the Chartered Society of Physiotherapists produced the ‘Get up and go: a guide to staying steady’ booklet, a guide to preventing falls. People are able to download the booklet from:</p><p><a href="http://www.csp.org.uk/publications/get-go-guide-staying-steady" target="_blank">http://www.csp.org.uk/publications/get-go-guide-staying-steady</a></p><p> </p><p>and the falls page of the NHS Choices website. Hard copies are also available upon request.</p><p> </p><p>PHE is also collaborating with the Centre for Ageing Better and the Chief Medical Officer to produce practical evidence based guidance on maintaining and improving muscle strength and balance. This is due to be published in autumn 2017.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-01T11:40:29.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692564/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692564/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692564/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Older People: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidance his Department makes available for elderly people on how to avoid harmful falls.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692565","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>A search of the Department’s Ministerial correspondence database has identified one item of correspondence received since 1 February 2016 about the adequacy of provision in accident and emergency departments for patients presenting with heart problems. We are not aware of any other representations.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-03-01T15:09:07.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692565/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692565/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692565/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Accident and Emergency Departments: Heart Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations his Department has received on the adequacy of provision in A&E departments for patients presenting with heart problems.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692566","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>Laboratory confirmed cases of hepatitis E infection are reported to Public Health England.</p><p> </p><p>The number of reported cases of hepatitis E in England and Wales reported to Public Health England by year (2012 to 2016) can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hepatitis-e-symptoms-transmission-prevention-treatment/hepatitis-e-symptoms-transmission-treatment-and-prevention" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hepatitis-e-symptoms-transmission-prevention-treatment/hepatitis-e-symptoms-transmission-treatment-and-prevention</a></p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-01T11:10:23.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692566/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692566/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692566/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Hepatitis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people have been diagnosed with hepatitis E in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692567","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>There are currently two antenatal and newborn screening programmes which aim to detect serious heart conditions; NHS Fetal Anomaly Screening Programme and NHS Newborn and Infant Physical Examination Screening Programme.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to this the UK National Screening Committee (UK NSC) has reviewed the evidence for two adult screening programmes; Atrial Fibrillation (AF) and risk of Sudden Cardiac Death (SCD). These programmes have not been recommended as there is insufficient evidence that they provide more benefit than harm.</p><p> </p><p>The UK NSC will review the evidence for AF and risk of SCD as part of its three year review cycle.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-01T10:44:38.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692567/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692567/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692567/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Heart Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps the NHS is taking to help detect hidden genetic heart defects or conditions.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692568","Department of Health","false","2017-02-24","<p>We have made no such assessment.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-02-24T14:01:46.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692568/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692568/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692568/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Alzheimer's Disease: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment the NHS has made of the potential merits of using laser technology to treat Alzheimer's disease in its early stages.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692569","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Department would not keep a record of any discussions clinical bodies have had with pharmaceutical companies.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-01T13:47:06.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692569/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692569/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692569/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Malaria: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions clinical bodies have had with pharmaceutical companies on the development of new malaria prophylactics.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692570","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>Both the ‘Five Year Forward view for Mental Health’ and ‘Achieving world-class cancer outcomes: a strategy for England 2015-2020’ recognise the close link between mental health problems and poor outcomes for long term physical health conditions including cancer.</p><p> </p><p>People with common mental health problems often have physical long term conditions. When mental and physical health problems are treated in an integrated way people can achieve better outcomes. NHS England is supporting 22 ‘Early Implementer’ projects across the country to lead the way in integrating psychological therapies with physical health care. Early implementer services are integrated into a number of different physical healthcare pathways including cancer.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has also committed to full roll out of the Recovery Package for cancer patients by 2020. Undertaking a Holistic Needs Assessment (HNA) and putting together a Care Plan are key parts of the Recovery Package that should be offered to a patient soon after their diagnosis and at the end of treatment. The HNA guides a conversation about the person’s holistic needs (physical, psychosocial, financial and social) in order to identify any concerns. Mental health concerns and emotional support needs should be picked up in this assessment and support offered.</p><p> </p><p>In December 2016, NHS England announced Transformation Funding of over £200 million available to Cancer Alliances over the next two years, specifically to support those areas of the Cancer Taskforce strategy that they estimated would need significant investment, including the Recovery Package.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-01T10:39:37.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692570/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692570/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692570/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Cancer: Depressive Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment the NHS has made of potential links between anxiety and depression and the onset of cancer; and what recent steps his Department has taken to promote wellbeing.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692571","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) published its draft updated guideline on Parkinson’s disease for consultation on 4 October. Stakeholders had until 15 November to respond. Stakeholders’ consultation comments and NICE’s responses will be published on NICE’s website alongside the final guideline. NICE currently expects to publish its final updated guidance in April 2017.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-01T13:40:45.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692571/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692571/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692571/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Parkinson's Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what opportunity stakeholders will have to respond to the NICE's draft updated guideline on the management of Parkinson's disease.","false","Biography information for Glyn Davies","Montgomeryshire","Glyn Davies","64880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692572","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Department has made no such assessment.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-01T13:48:03.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692572/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692572/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692572/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Antidepressants: Side Effects","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the costs to the public purse of the treatment of side effects from long-term use of antidepressants.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","64853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692573","Department of Health","false","2017-02-24","<p>Receiving rapid diagnoses and medical treatment is vital for the survival and recovery of stroke patients. Across England there is a variation in the level of care for survivors, and there is strong evidence that more specialist stroke units providing high quality care 24 hours a day, seven days a week will save more lives and support recovery. Data from the Sentinel Stroke National Audit Programme has shown that there is a strong relationship between the number of patients and the quality of care from the greater experience these more practiced clinicians have, access to costly specialised facilities and equipment available.</p><p> </p><p>In 2014 NHS England published the NHS Five Year Forward View. This is being implemented through 44 local Sustainability and Transformation Plans (STPs). These plans are partnerships between local National Health Service organisations, councils and others who are now working more closely together than ever.</p><p> </p><p>Plans are at various stages of development for stroke services. NHS England’s National Clinical Director for stroke continues to support partners within each of the 44 areas to develop their plans to achieve the best outcomes for stroke care. The arrangement of stroke services is a matter for local decision makers using the best clinical evidence available. This may include the creation of specialist stroke services, where clinically appropriate and supported by decision makers, staff, residents and transport infrastructure. NHS and local government partners are currently engaging communities on their draft plans, and no change to services people currently receive will be made without consultation where it is required. Each organisation collaborating on an STP retains its usual duties to engage local people on any new proposals. There are longstanding assurance processes in place to make sure this happens.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-02-24T13:42:29.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692573/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692573/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692573/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Strokes: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 23 November 2016 to Question 53721, what estimate he has made of the number of sustainable transformation plan areas with stroke service reconfiguration in their plans.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","64864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692574","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has published a number of clinical guidelines for mental health conditions that recommend psychological therapies. NICE’s guidelines on this topic, recommendations on the use of specific drugs, interventional procedures and computerised Cognitive Behavioural Therapy can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/conditions-and-diseases/mental-health-and-behavioural-conditions/depression" target="_blank">https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/conditions-and-diseases/mental-health-and-behavioural-conditions/depression</a></p><p> </p><p>Clinical guidelines represent best practice and should be taken fully into account by clinicians.</p><p> </p><p>The Improving Access to Psychological Therapies (IAPT) programme provides NICE approved services to people in England with common mental health conditions including depression. Since the start of the IAPT Programme in 2008, more than four million adults have entered the IAPT programme. Of that four million, over 2.7 million have completed treatment and over 950,000 are in recovery.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-01T13:44:21.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692574/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692574/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692574/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Depressive Illnesses: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the accessibility of NICE-recommended treatments for patients at risk of recurrent depression in England.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","64850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692575","Department of Health","false","2017-02-24","<p>The Department does not issue guidance to clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) on the commissioning of stroke-specific services. NHS England is responsible for issuing guidance to CCGs on commissioning services.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-02-24T12:37:30.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692575/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692575/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692575/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Strokes: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 23 November 2016 to Question 53721, what guidance his Department has given to clinical commissioning groups on the commissioning of stroke-specific services.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","64867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692576","Department of Health","false","2017-02-24","<p>The information requested is not collected centrally.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-02-24T10:13:47.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692576/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692576/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692576/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Mental Health Services: Acute Beds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many acute mental health beds there were, and what the occupancy rate of such beds was, in Birmingham and Solihull Mental Health Foundation Trust in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","64887"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692577","Department of Health","false","2017-02-24","<p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State has not had any such discussions. NHS England leads on the commissioning of services and related discussions with health providers in local areas.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-02-24T10:35:28.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692577/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692577/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692577/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Hospitals: Warrington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with health providers in Warrington on proposals for a new hospital for Warrington; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","64909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692578","Department of Health","false","2017-02-24","<p>Commissioners take into account a range of factors when deciding where services should be placed. These include population need, geographical factors, other available services and service sustainability.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-02-24T10:37:03.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692578/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692578/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692578/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Hospitals: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what factors are taken into account when deciding on the location of proposed new hospitals; and what weighting is given to each of those factors.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","64910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692579","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>Capita is currently piloting a barcode tracking system for medical records in West Yorkshire. The pilot is intended to ensure that the system is proven before being rolled out across England. All feedback and evidence is being carefully reviewed by NHS England. NHS England’s interim assessment is that this system is working well and has improved the speed of the movement of records. A full review of the system is expected to be completed in the spring of 2017 after which a decision on the roll-out across England will be made.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","64877","2017-03-01T13:46:07.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692579/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692579/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692579/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Medical Records: West Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment has been made of the effectiveness of the new records movement service being piloted in West Yorkshire by Capita.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","64876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692580","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>Capita is currently piloting a barcode tracking system for medical records in West Yorkshire. The pilot is intended to ensure that the system is proven before being rolled out across England. All feedback and evidence is being carefully reviewed by NHS England. NHS England’s interim assessment is that this system is working well and has improved the speed of the movement of records. A full review of the system is expected to be completed in the spring of 2017 after which a decision on the roll-out across England will be made.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","64876","2017-03-01T13:46:07.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692580/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692580/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692580/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Medical Records: West Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans the Government has to extend the new records movement service, currently being piloted in West Yorkshire, to the rest of the country.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","64877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692581","Department of Health","false","2017-02-24","<p>When making decisions the Prescribed Specialised Services Advisory Group (PSSAG) must consider four factors:</p><p> </p><p>- the number of individuals who require the provision of the service or facility;</p><p>- the cost of providing the service or facility;</p><p>- the number of persons able to provide the service or facility; and</p><p>- the financial implications for clinical commissioning groups if they were required to arrange for the provision of the service or facility.</p><p> </p><p>PSSAG therefore requests that any proposals put forward for its consideration include data which supports informed decision making in these areas. If the group does not feel that there is sufficient data to reach a decision, it may request further information to enable it to do so at a later date. More information can be found at the following address:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/prescribed-specialised-services-advisory-group-pssag" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/prescribed-specialised-services-advisory-group-pssag</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Clinical Reference Groups (CRGs) are not decision making groups.</p><p> </p><p>However CRGs collate a large amount of data to consider when providing their clinical advice and utilise when making recommendations relating to commissioning.</p><p> </p><p>From a clinical commissioning policy perspective, CRGs gather and analyse data and intelligence that is relevant to the treatment proposal they are considering, such as Individual Funding Request activity, a summary of clinical evidence and related trial statistics. They would consider prevalence and incidence data sources, search clinical databases and registries for relevant data and collect data on clinical outcomes and clinical quality aspects. The CRG would also take account of patient experience information and relevant financial information.</p><p> </p><p>Similar data sources would also be used to support the development of service specifications and to inform the work on service reviews.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-02-24T13:40:13.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692581/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692581/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692581/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what data (a) Clinical Reference Groups and (b) the Prescribed Specialised Services Advisory Group are required to collect and consider in the course of making their decisions.","false","Biography information for Sir Kevin Barron","Rother Valley","Kevin Barron","64912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692582","Department of Health","false","2017-02-24","<p>We would expect providers and commissioners to ensure that any service change is in the interests of high quality patient care. During transition periods local commissioners and providers should ensure that high standards of patient care are maintained for patients affected by the changes.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has assessed the Newcastle Upon Tyne Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust against its standards for congenital heart disease services and concluded that it does not meet the 2019 paediatric co-location requirements or currently have a realistic plan to do so by April 2019.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has asked the Trust to give due consideration as to how this standard could be achieved.</p><p> </p><p>The Trust has stated that it is committed to undertaking an option appraisal with regard to the co-location of Paediatric Heart Services with other children’s services. The full range of options is not yet determined, but the appraisal will take full consideration of any impact on patient care.</p><p> </p><p>These considerations are at a very early stage and do not form part of the proposals recently set out by NHS England in its consultation on implementing Congenital Heart Disease standards.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","64937 ; 64940","2017-02-24T10:33:45.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692582/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692582/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692582/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Heart Diseases: Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on patient care of moving Newcastle's Child and Adult Heart Surgery Unit from the Freeman Hospital to the Royal Victoria Infirmary.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","64936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692583","Department of Health","false","2017-02-24","<p>We would expect providers and commissioners to ensure that any service change is in the interests of high quality patient care. During transition periods local commissioners and providers should ensure that high standards of patient care are maintained for patients affected by the changes.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has assessed the Newcastle Upon Tyne Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust against its standards for congenital heart disease services and concluded that it does not meet the 2019 paediatric co-location requirements or currently have a realistic plan to do so by April 2019.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has asked the Trust to give due consideration as to how this standard could be achieved.</p><p> </p><p>The Trust has stated that it is committed to undertaking an option appraisal with regard to the co-location of Paediatric Heart Services with other children’s services. The full range of options is not yet determined, but the appraisal will take full consideration of any impact on patient care.</p><p> </p><p>These considerations are at a very early stage and do not form part of the proposals recently set out by NHS England in its consultation on implementing Congenital Heart Disease standards.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","64936 ; 64940","2017-02-24T10:33:45.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692583/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692583/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692583/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","NHS: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps the Government takes to ensure minimal disruption to quality of service when NHS services are moved from one site to another.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","64937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692584","Department of Health","false","2017-03-01","<p>There is no maximum length of time for which data can be collected on treatments funded from the Cancer Drugs Fund (CDF). The duration in the CDF for a cancer drug is determined on an individual basis by the time required for such data development/collection to take place. This will depend on the disease concerned, the data that needs to be examined, the clinical trials that may be already running, and considerations of cancer treatment pathways in England. The time that a drug stays in the CDF is therefore individually assessed and agreed with NHS England, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence and the company concerned. The timeframe will normally be up to two years, but will be considered on a case by case basis.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-01T13:42:43.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692584/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692584/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692584/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 20 February 2017 to Question 63820, if he will take steps to increase the maximum length of time for which data can be collected on treatments funded from the Cancer Drugs Fund from two to three years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Pauline Latham","Mid Derbyshire","Pauline Latham","64926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692585","Department of Health","false","2017-02-24","<p>We would expect providers and commissioners to ensure that any service change is in the interests of high quality patient care. During transition periods local commissioners and providers should ensure that high standards of patient care are maintained for patients affected by the changes.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has assessed the Newcastle Upon Tyne Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust against its standards for congenital heart disease services and concluded that it does not meet the 2019 paediatric co-location requirements or currently have a realistic plan to do so by April 2019.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has asked the Trust to give due consideration as to how this standard could be achieved.</p><p> </p><p>The Trust has stated that it is committed to undertaking an option appraisal with regard to the co-location of Paediatric Heart Services with other children’s services. The full range of options is not yet determined, but the appraisal will take full consideration of any impact on patient care.</p><p> </p><p>These considerations are at a very early stage and do not form part of the proposals recently set out by NHS England in its consultation on implementing Congenital Heart Disease standards.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","64936 ; 64937","2017-02-24T10:33:45.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692585/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692585/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692585/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-21","NHS: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent representations he has received on the public consultation process for moving NHS services between two locations.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","64940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692586","Home Office","false","2017-02-27","<p>Access to controlled drugs for legitimate medicinal (or exceptionally for industrial purposes) is permitted through the Misuse of Drugs Regulations 2001.</p><p> </p><p>There is a clear regime in place, administered by the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA), to enable medicines (including those containing controlled drugs such as cannabis) to be developed, licensed and made available for medicinal use to patients in the UK. For example, the cannabis-based medicine ‘sativex’ has been granted Marketing Authorisation in the UK by the MHRA for the treatment of spasticity due to multiple sclerosis. Sativex was rigorously tested for its safety and efficacy before receiving approval for this application.</p><p> </p><p>The MHRA is open to considering marketing approval applications for other medicinal cannabis products should a product be developed. As happened in the case of sativex, the Home Office will consider issuing a licence to enable trials of any new medicine providing it complies with appropriate ethical approvals.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-27T14:40:40.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692586/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692586/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692586/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Cannabis: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the oral contribution of the then Minister for Policing, Crime and Criminal Justice on 20 January 2016, Official Report, column 1479, what progress her Department has made on the use of cannabis for the purposes of medicinal research.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","64923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692587","Home Office","false","2017-02-27","<p>We are working with the Greek and Italian authorities, UNHCR and non-governmental organisations to identify children from Greece and Italy who may qualify for transfer to the UK. We have seconded an expert to Greece to support these efforts, in addition to our long-standing secondee in Italy. We have established a dedicated Home Office Dublin Regulation team to lead on family reunion cases for unaccompanied children.</p><p>We will consider all requests from Member States, including Greece and Italy, to take responsibility for unaccompanied asylum seeking children or other family members where there are grounds to do so under the Dublin Regulation.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-27T14:39:10.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692587/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692587/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692587/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to proactively identify unaccompanied refugee children and vulnerable families in Greece and Italy who can be brought to join family members in the UK; and what use her Department has made of the discretionary powers under the Dublin III Regulations to take charge of such children and families.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","64924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692588","Home Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>The information requested is not collected centrally.</p><p>The figures in the press release of 29 December provided an early snapshot of enforcement activity since the commencement of the Psychoactive Substances Act (PSA). They were based on voluntary data returned to the National Police Chiefs’ Council by 44 police forces in the United Kingdom covering the period 26 May to 26 November 2016.</p><p>We are undertaking a formal review of the Act and the review will report its findings by late 2018.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","64878 ; 64907","2017-03-01T16:10:48.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692588/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692588/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692588/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Drugs: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to her Department's press release of 29 December 2016, psychoactive substances ban six months on: almost 500 arrests and first convictions, of the 500 people arrested how many were (a) charged with an offence and (b) prosecuted with an offence under the Psychoactive Substances Act 2016; how many of those prosecutions were (i) unsuccessful and (ii) successful; and of the four prosecutions that resulted in prison sentences, if she will list for each case (A) the grounds for prosecution, (B) how the defendants pleaded, (C) whether those defendants were found guilty of any other offences and (D) what sentence was given by the court.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","64918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692589","Home Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>Several licensing authorities ran consultations on the introduction of an Early Morning Alcohol Restriction Order (EMRO) between 2013 and early 2014. No consultation resulted in the introduction of an EMRO.</p><p>The Home Office sought feedback from the licensing authorities involved in those consultations, as well as from others that had not actively considered an EMRO. Many licensing authorities felt that they would only use the EMRO as a last resort if other methods to reduce alcohol-related problems had failed, and did not feel it an appropriate means to reduce alcohol-related problems in their area.</p><p>Some felt that an EMRO could be perceived by members of public and businesses as labelling an area as having high alcohol-related crime or being unsafe. Some felt that it conflicted with the need to support local businesses and increase economic growth, and preferred alternative approaches such as local partnership working and voluntary agreements, or reviewing individual premises licences.</p><p>They also highlighted practical issues with implementation: licensing authorities considered the process to be onerous, and this in itself was a barrier to considering an EMRO.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","64900","2017-02-24T14:48:56.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692589/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692589/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692589/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Licensing Laws","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the reasons why no local authority has yet implemented an early morning alcohol restriction order.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","64899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692590","Home Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>The information requested is not collected centrally.</p><p>The figures in the press release of 29 December provided an early snapshot of enforcement activity since the commencement of the Psychoactive Substances Act (PSA). They were based on voluntary data returned to the National Police Chiefs’ Council by 44 police forces in the United Kingdom covering the period 26 May to 26 November 2016.</p><p>We are undertaking a formal review of the Act and the review will report its findings by late 2018.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","64878 ; 64918","2017-03-01T16:10:49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692590/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692590/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692590/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Drugs: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many premises and prohibition (a) notices and (b) orders have been issued since the Psychoactive Substances Act 2016 came into force.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","64907"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692591","Home Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>Several licensing authorities ran consultations on the introduction of an Early Morning Alcohol Restriction Order (EMRO) between 2013 and early 2014. No consultation resulted in the introduction of an EMRO.</p><p>The Home Office sought feedback from the licensing authorities involved in those consultations, as well as from others that had not actively considered an EMRO. Many licensing authorities felt that they would only use the EMRO as a last resort if other methods to reduce alcohol-related problems had failed, and did not feel it an appropriate means to reduce alcohol-related problems in their area.</p><p>Some felt that an EMRO could be perceived by members of public and businesses as labelling an area as having high alcohol-related crime or being unsafe. Some felt that it conflicted with the need to support local businesses and increase economic growth, and preferred alternative approaches such as local partnership working and voluntary agreements, or reviewing individual premises licences.</p><p>They also highlighted practical issues with implementation: licensing authorities considered the process to be onerous, and this in itself was a barrier to considering an EMRO.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","64899","2017-02-24T14:48:56.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692591/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692591/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692591/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Licensing Laws","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what representations her Department has received from local authorities on the merits of early morning alcohol restriction orders.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","64900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692592","Home Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>The information requested is not collected centrally.</p><p>The figures in the press release of 29 December provided an early snapshot of enforcement activity since the commencement of the Psychoactive Substances Act (PSA). They were based on voluntary data returned to the National Police Chiefs’ Council by 44 police forces in the United Kingdom covering the period 26 May to 26 November 2016.</p><p>We are undertaking a formal review of the Act and the review will report its findings by late 2018.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","64907 ; 64918","2017-03-01T16:10:48.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692592/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692592/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692592/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to her Department's press release of 29 December 2016, psychoactive substances ban six months on: almost 500 arrests and first convictions, what the alleged offences were for each person arrested; and which police force carried out each arrest.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","64878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692593","Home Office","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Modern Slavery taskforce, chaired by the Prime Minister, is coordinating activity across law enforcement agencies to ensure that powers available to disrupt, deter and prevent human trafficking are used to best effect.</p><p>This includes powers under Section 12 of the Modern Slavery Act 2015 to detain vehicles, ships and aircraft from those arrested on suspicion of human trafficking offences and wider powers available under the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-27T14:42:48.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692593/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692593/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692593/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to encourage the seizure of assets of human traffickers at the point of arrest, rather than conviction.","false","Biography information for Lord Garnier","Harborough","Sir Edward Garnier","64829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692594","Home Office","false","2017-03-02","<p>On February 8, the Government announced that we will transfer the specified number of 350 children to the UK under section 67 of the Immigration Act following consultation with local authorities on capacity. We ran a full consultation process, with regional events in every part of England, one in Scotland and one in Wales. Over 400 local authority representatives attended the regional events. Any further places offered by local authorities will be gratefully received, and we will use them to fulfil our existing commitments, including ensuring a fairer distribution of children between local authorities through the National Transfer Scheme.</p><p>In July 2016 the Government significantly increased the funding it provides to local authorities who look after unaccompanied asylum-seeking children. Local authorities now receive £41,610 per annum year for each unaccompanied asylum-seeking child aged under 16 and £33,215 per annum for unaccompanied asylum-seeking child aged 16 and 17. This represents a 20% and 28% increase in funding respectively. In addition, the Government went further and also increased the funding it provides to local authorities for those young people who turn 18 and go on to attract leaving care support by 33%. We will be working with local authority partners to conduct a review of our funding rates and remain fully committed to maintaining the current rates.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-02T18:00:04.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692594/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692594/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692594/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to consult with local authorities on whether they can make more places available under Section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","64871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692595","Home Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>We have seconded an expert to Greece to support these efforts, and are working in conjunction with the Greek authorities, UNHCR and NGOs to identify children whose best interests may be served by a transfer to the UK under section 67 of the Immigration Act, pending the publication of the basis on which the transfers will be made.</p><p>In Italy, our long-standing secondee is also working closely with the Italian authorities. Our secondees are also working to support the timely and efficient operation of the Dublin Regulation, in order to ensure that children with close family in the UK can be reunited. Furthermore, the UK has established a £10 million Refugee Children’s Fund to support the needs of vulnerable refugee and migrant children arriving in Europe.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-01T16:13:58.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692595/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692595/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692595/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that children outside of formal camps in Greece and Italy are assessed for relocation to the UK under the Dublin Regulation and Section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","64872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692596","Home Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>We will announce in due course the basis on which further children will be transferred from Europe to the UK, where it is in their best interests, under section 67 of the Immigration Act to the specified number.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-01T16:02:50.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692596/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692596/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692596/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the eligibility criteria for the 150 remaining places announced under Section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016, and for any further transfers to the UK, will prioritise individual vulnerability and the best interests of children.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","64873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692597","Home Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>Licensing requirements for sexual entertainment venues are set out in the Policing and Crime Act 2009. The absence of a right of appeal against a local authority licensing committee's decision is counter-balanced by the additional conditions prospective licensees must satisfy such as having regard to the characteristics of the area and the use to which other premises in the vicinity are put.</p><p>When considering an application for the grant, renewal or transfer of a licence the appropriate authority should have regard to any observations submitted to it by the chief officer of police and any objections that they have received from anyone else within 28 days of the application. Any person can object to an application but the objection should be relevant to the grounds set out in paragraph 12 of Schedule 3 to the Local Government (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1982 for refusing a licence. As licences must be applied for annually, licensing committees are able to take into account any relevant objections received during this time.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-03-01T16:23:17.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692597/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692597/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692597/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Sex Establishments: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 6 February 2017 to Question 62659, on sex establishments: licensing, for what reason there is no right given to objectors to appeal against a local authority licensing committee's decision to grant a sexual entertainment licence.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","64808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692598","Home Office","false","2017-02-27","<p>We are working across Government to identify and develop options to shape our future immigration system.</p><p>Parliament will have an important role to play in this and we will ensure businesses and communities have the opportunity to contribute their views.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","64852","2017-02-27T14:46:32.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692598/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692598/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692598/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Visas: Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the merits of short-term study visas for EU citizens wishing to study in the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","64851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692599","Home Office","false","2017-02-27","<p>We are working across Government to identify and develop options to shape our future immigration system.</p><p>Parliament will have an important role to play in this and we will ensure businesses and communities have the opportunity to contribute their views.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","64851","2017-02-27T14:46:32.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692599/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692599/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692599/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Visas: Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of this effect of any changes to the short-term study visa system arising from the UK's decision to leave the EU, on the number of foreign nationals seeking to study English.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","64852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692600","Home Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>Police force figures collated and published by the National Police Chiefs’ Council indicate that police cells in England and Wales were used as places of safety under section 136 of the Mental Health Act 1983 a total of 2,100 times in 2015/16 – a 54 per cent reduction on the previous year.</p><p>In addition, in 2015/16 the Home Office requested trial data from police forces in England and Wales on the use of section 136 of the Mental Health Act 1983, including more detailed information about the people detained and to what place of safety they were subsequently taken. 15 forces voluntarily submitted data in response to the pilot data collection.</p><p>On the basis of these data, the Home Office published experimental statistics to give an indicative picture of the proportion of instances where a police cell was used as a place of safety following detention under section 136 of the Mental Health Act 1983. These data can be found in Annex B of the statistical publication ‘Police powers and procedures’: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-powers-and-procedures-england-and-wales-year-ending-31-march-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-powers-and-procedures-england-and-wales-year-ending-31-march-2016</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-03-01T16:20:31.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692600/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692600/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692600/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Compulsorily Detained Psychiatric Patients: Police Custody","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many recorded instances there were of police cells being used as places of safety for people detained under section 136 of the Mental Health Act 1983 in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","64804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692601","Home Office","false","2017-02-27","<p>Data on the number of convicted human traffickers returned to their countries of origin to serve the sentence and whose assets (whether in the UK or overseas) have also been seized to compensate victims, police forces and HM Treasury is not collated centrally.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-27T14:30:05.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692601/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692601/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692601/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people convicted of human trafficking in the UK who returned to their country of origin to serve their sentence have had their assets (a) in the UK or (b) overseas seized to compensate (i) victims of trafficking, (ii) police forces and (iii) HM Treasury; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lord Garnier","Harborough","Sir Edward Garnier","64701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692602","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-01","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-03-01T16:22:56.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692602/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692602/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692602/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-21","Alternatives to Prosecution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how often each out of court disposals panel met in each constabulary area in England in 2016; how many cases were examined by each of those panels during that period; how many of those cases (a) related to a caution, (b) were dealt with by restorative justice, (c) related to a youth caution, (d) were dealt with by a fixed penalty notice and caution, (e) were dealt with by youth triage and (f) were dealt with by a conditional caution during that period; and how many of those cases related to (i) youths and (ii) adults.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","64766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692603","Home Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>The Minister of State for Immigration replied on 23 February 2017.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-24T13:05:10.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692603/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692603/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692603/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to reply to the letter from the hon. Member for Walsall North of 16 January 2017 on behalf of a constituent, on asylum claims from people fleeing torture and repressive regimes.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","64777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692604","Home Office","false","2017-02-27","<p>The responsibilities in respect of financial management of police authorities and, since their creation by the Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2012, local policing bodies are set out in legislation and financial Codes of Practice.</p><p> </p><p>Prior to the creation of Police and Crime Commissioners, Police Authorities were required to adhere to the Code of Practice on Financial Management for policing, which was issued in October 2000 under Section 39 of the Police Act 1996. This Code set out the requirements and obligations of police authorities and has since been withdrawn.</p><p> </p><p>The Financial Management Code of Practice (FMCP), published in October 2013, provides clarity around the financial governance arrangements within the police in England and Wales. It sets out the responsibilities of the Chief Finance Officer of the PCC and of the Chief Constable who each have a personal fiduciary duty by virtue of their appointment as the person responsible for proper financial administration under the Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011. This includes requirements and formal powers to safeguard lawfulness and propriety in expenditure.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/252720/fm_code_of_practice.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/252720/fm_code_of_practice.pdf</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","64770","2017-02-27T11:40:54.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692604/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692604/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692604/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Cleveland Police Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what measures were in place to ensure that members of the Cleveland Police Authority were required to declare any relevant business interests arising from procurement or outsourcing partnership arrangements instigated by Cleveland Police prior to Operation Sacristy.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","64772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692605","Home Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>A criminal record for the offence of sending an indecent image will only result where the offender, child or adult, is charged to court (and found guilty) or cautioned by the police. Where the police resolve such cases by other means no criminal record is established.</p><p>The Government is clear that where a crime has been committed it should be recorded as such. This is critical to understand the extent of this issue, to identify any pattern of repeat or high-risk behaviour, and providing transparency and accountability.</p><p>However, the police have wide discretion as to how to address such behaviour. Working with the National Police Chiefs’ Council and the Department for Education new guidance has been issued to police and schools in relation to children sending indecent images and which has a focus on safeguarding. We have introduced a new outcome for police to apply in cases where they consider it appropriate to undertake no criminal investigation and which will highlight that any subsequent disclosure should only be in the most exceptional cases.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","64788","2017-02-24T13:11:31.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692605/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692605/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692605/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Sexting: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of reports that young people are receiving criminal records for sending indecent images without having been charged with an offence.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","64787"
