"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692609","Home Office","false","2017-03-01","<p>There are no Premium Lines within the Home Office, so there has been no revenue in the last five years.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-03-01T15:58:51.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692609/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692609/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692609/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Home Office: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much income has been accrued to her Department from premium rate telephone lines in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","64740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692610","Home Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>Building upon Northern Ireland's positive contribution to the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement scheme the Home Office continues to be in contact with the Northern Ireland Executive at ministerial and official level including discussions regarding unaccompanied asylum seeking children</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-24T14:35:41.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692610/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692610/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692610/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Asylum: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions she has had with the Northern Ireland Executive on the potential to increase the number of unaccompanied child refugees received by Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","64756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692611","Home Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>Operation Sacristy was an investigation that was conducted independently of the Home Office involving a number of organisations and agencies, including the Independent Police Complaints Commission (IPCC). As such we cannot provide specific detail on this operation or its terms of reference.</p><p>In 2014 Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary (HMIC) reported on the extent to which Cleveland Police Force had put in place arrangements to ensure its workforce acts with integrity as part of its <em>Police Integrity and Corruption Programme</em> available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.justiceinspectorates.gov.uk/hmic/wp-content/uploads/cleveland-crime-and-integrity.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.justiceinspectorates.gov.uk/hmic/wp-content/uploads/cleveland-crime-and-integrity.pdf</a></p><p>HMIC produced further findings as part of its 2016 Legitimacy programme, which included an assessment of how well the force ensures that its workforce behaves ethically and lawfully. The 2016 Cleveland report is available: <a href="https://www.justiceinspectorates.gov.uk/hmic/wp-content/uploads/peel-police-legitimacy-2016-cleveland.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.justiceinspectorates.gov.uk/hmic/wp-content/uploads/peel-police-legitimacy-2016-cleveland.pdf</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","64760 ; 64771","2017-02-24T15:04:34.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692611/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692611/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692611/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Cleveland Police Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions have taken place between HM Inspectorate of Constabulary and the Chief Constable of Cleveland Police on the terms of reference for Operation Sacristy; and what representations she has received on potential concerns raised by the Chief Constable of Cleveland Police on those terms of reference during those negotiations.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","64757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692612","Home Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>We do not comment on operational decisions by forces investigating crime and therefore cannot provide specific detail on this operation. The management of witnesses during any investigation by a law enforcement agency should be compliant with the Victims Code (2015) and Witness Charter (2013), this ensures a minimum level of service to all victims and witnesses.</p><p>Where intimidation is identified, measures can be taken in accordance with the Victims’ Code and Witness Charter to mitigate risk. Where the risk to a victim or witness is deemed serious and ongoing, management may be provided by the UK Protected Persons Service (UKPPS). The UKPPS can neither confirm nor deny individuals as protected persons to preserve their anonymity and safety.</p><p>Operational decisions in relation to the retention of evidence by law enforcement agencies is governed by the Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984 and Criminal Procedure and Investigations Act 1996.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","64759","2017-02-24T14:59:47.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692612/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692612/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692612/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Cleveland Police Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department took to protect witnesses during the Operation Sacristy investigation into corruption allegations at Cleveland Police Authority.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","64758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692613","Home Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>We do not comment on operational decisions by forces investigating crime and therefore cannot provide specific detail on this operation. The management of witnesses during any investigation by a law enforcement agency should be compliant with the Victims Code (2015) and Witness Charter (2013), this ensures a minimum level of service to all victims and witnesses.</p><p>Where intimidation is identified, measures can be taken in accordance with the Victims’ Code and Witness Charter to mitigate risk. Where the risk to a victim or witness is deemed serious and ongoing, management may be provided by the UK Protected Persons Service (UKPPS). The UKPPS can neither confirm nor deny individuals as protected persons to preserve their anonymity and safety.</p><p>Operational decisions in relation to the retention of evidence by law enforcement agencies is governed by the Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984 and Criminal Procedure and Investigations Act 1996.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","64758","2017-02-24T14:59:47.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692613/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692613/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692613/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-21","Cleveland Police Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she has taken to ensure that (a) evidence was not destroyed and (b) witnesses were not intimidated by members of Cleveland Police during Operation Sacristy.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","64759"
